ons (English footballer)|Mick Lyons]] (2002)\n* {{flagicon|MAR}} [[Karim Bencherifa]] (2003\u201304)\n* {{flagicon|Bosnia}} [[Amir Alagic]] (2005)\n* {{flagicon|BRU}} [[Mohd Ali Mustafa]] (2006)\n* {{flagicon|KOR}} [[Kwon Oh-Son]] (2008)\n* {{flagicon|CRO}} [[Vjeran Simuni\u0107]] (2008\u201309)\n* {{flagicon|BRU}} [[Mohd Ali Mustafa]] (2009)\n* {{flagicon|BRU}} [[Dayem Hj Ali]] (2011)\n* {{flagicon|KOR}} [[Kwon Oh-Son]] (2012\u201313)\n* {{flagicon|CRO}} [[Vjeran Simuni\u0107]] (2013\u201314)\n* {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Steve Kean]] (2014)\n* {{flagicon|SIN}} [[Mike Wong Mun Heng|Mike Wong]] (2014\u20132016)\n* {{flagicon|KOR}} [[Kwon Oh-Son]] (2016)\n* {{flagicon|SIN}} [[Stephen Ng Heng Seng|Stephen Ng]] (2017)\n* {{flagicon|KOR}} [[Kwon Oh-Son]] (2018)\n* {{flagicon|NED}} [[Robbie Servais]] (2019)\n* {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Paul Smalley]] (2019\u2013)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Honours==\n* '''[[Borneo Cup]]\n** '''Winner (4):''' 1968, 1981, 1987, 1988\n* '''[[Football at the Brunei Merdeka Games|Brunei Merdeka Games]]\n** '''Runners-up (1):''' [[Football at the 1985 Brunei Merdeka Games|1985]]\n* '''Philippines International Cup'''\n** '''Third Place (1):'''1993'''\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Football in Brunei}}\n{{AFC teams}}\n{{National sports teams of Brunei}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brunei National Football Team}}\n[[Category:Asian national association football teams]]\n[[Category:Brunei national football team| ]]\n[[Category:National sports teams of Brunei|Football]]\n", "name_user": "84.118.61.220", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brunei_national_football_team"}
{"title_page": "Social Security Scotland", "text_new": "{{Infobox government agency\n|agency_name     = Social Security Scotland<br>T\u00e8arainteachd Sh\u00f2isealta Alba\n|type            = [[Executive agencies of the Scottish Government|Executive Agency]]\n|logo            = Social Security Scotland logo.svg\n|logo_width      =\n|logo_caption    =\n|seal            =\n|seal_width      =\n|seal_caption    =\n|picture         =\n|picture_width   =\n|picture_caption =\n|formed          = 2018\n|preceding1      = [[Department for Work and Pensions]]\n|preceding2      = [[Secretary of State for Work and Pensions]]\n<!-- (etc.) -->\n|dissolved       =\n|superseding     =\n|jurisdiction    = [[Scotland]]\n|headquarters    = [[Dundee]]<br>[[Glasgow]]\n|coordinates     =\n|motto           = Dignity, fairness, respect.\n|employees       =\n|budget          =\n|minister1_name  = [[Shirley-Anne Somerville|Shirley-Anne Somerville MSP]]\n|minister1_pfo   = [[Cabinet Secretary for Social Security and Older People|Cabinet Secretary for Social Security]]\n|minister2_name  =\n|minister2_pfo   =\n<!-- (etc.) -->\n|deputyminister1_name  = [[Christina McKelvie|Christina McKelvie MSP]]\n|deputyminister1_pfo   = [[Minister for Older People and Equalities]]\n|deputyminister2_name  =\n|deputyminister2_pfo   =\n<!-- (etc.) -->\n|chief1_name     = David Wallace\n|chief1_position = Chief Executive\n|website         = {{URL|https://www.socialsecurity.gov.scot/|Social Security Scotland}}\n|footnotes       =\n|map             =\n|map_width       =\n|map_caption     =\n}}\n\n'''Social Security Scotland''' ([[Scottish Gaelic language|Scottish Gaelic]]: ''T\u00e8arainteachd Sh\u00f2isealta Alba'') is an executive agency of the [[Scottish Government]] with responsibility for [[Social security in Scotland|social security]] provision.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-43885731|title=Holyrood approves social security bill|last=BBC|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe [[Scottish Parliament]] was re-established in 1999 with legislative authority over many areas of social policy. However, social security remained a reserved matter of the [[UK Government]] through the [[Department for Work and Pensions]].  The [[Smith Commission]] following the \u2018No\u2019 vote to independence in the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|2014 referendum]] recommended that authority over several areas of social security be transferred to the Scottish Parliament under a revised devolution settlement for Scotland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.parliament.scot/ResearchBriefingsAndFactsheets/S4/SB_15-07_The_Smith_Commission_Welfare_Proposals.pdf|title=The Smith Commission's Welfare Proposals - Scottish Parliament|last=SPICe - Scottish Parliament|first=|date=21 January 2015|website=Scottish Parliament|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis was put into statue through the [[Scotland Act 2016]].\n\n==Legislation==\n{{Main|Social Security (Scotland) Act 2018}}\n\nWith the Scotland Act 2016 transferring authority over some elements of social security, the Scottish Government introduced the Social Security (Scotland) Bill.  This Bill introduced a different approach to administering social security in Scotland compared to the approach of the United Kingdom.  The Bill set out 8 principles of social security, putting into statute that social security is a human right, it is to be delivered as a public service and that it is to contribute to the reducing of poverty and provide dignity and respect to Scottish citizens.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-43885731|title=Holyrood approves social security bill|date=2018-04-25|access-date=2019-10-04|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe Bill sets out the need for a Scottish social security charter, which sets out the expectations of Scottish Ministers when developing social security policy, the expectations of Social Security Scotland when administering policies, and the expectations on individuals who are receiving assistance from Social Security Scotland.\n\nThe Bill established the Scottish Commission on Social Security, which is a corporate body independent of the Scottish Government.  The Commission's purpose is to scrutinise Scottish Government policy decisions and to ensure that the Scottish Government and Social Security Scotland are fulfilling the legal requirements under the Bill. \n\nThis Bill was passed on 25 April 2018 and received Royal Assent on 1 June 2018 as the [[Social Security (Scotland) Act 2018]]. It is the first Scotland wide social security agency in the nation's history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2018/9/enacted/data.htm|title=Social Security (Scotland) Act 2018|website=www.legislation.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==Ministers==\n\nThe Minister of the Scottish Government with responsibility for Social Security Scotland is the [[Cabinet Secretary for Social Security and Older People]], supported by the [[Minister for Older People and Equalities]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/about/who-runs-government/cabinet-and-ministers/|title=Cabinet and ministers - gov.scot|website=www.gov.scot|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"  cellpadding=\"6\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 0 0 0 1em; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaaaaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; \" \n|colspan=\"8\"|\n=== Minister for Social Security===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|[[Jeane Freeman]]\n| [[File:JeaneFreemanMSP.jpg|60px]]\n| 18 May 2016\n| 26 June 2018\n|[[Scottish National Party]]\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|[[Nicola Sturgeon]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"8\"|\n=== Cabinet Secretary for Social Security and Older People ===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|[[Shirley-Anne Somerville]]\n| [[File:Minister for Further Education, Higher Education and Science, Shirley Anne Sommerville.png|60px]]\n| 26 June 2018\n| ''incumbent''\n|[[Scottish National Party]]\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|[[Nicola Sturgeon]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Benefits==\n\n===Best Start Grant===\n[[Best Start Grant]] replaces the Sure Start Maternity Grant and is made up of three payments: Pregnancy and Baby Payment, Early Learning Payment, and School Age Payment. Best Start Foods is also under the Best Start Grant umbrella. The benefits are aimed at providing parents or carers who receive certain benefits or tax credits with extra financial support during key stages of a child's life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/policies/social-security/best-start-grant/|title=Social security: Best Start Grant - gov.scot|website=www.gov.scot|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n===Funeral Support Payment===\n[[Funeral Support Payment]] replaces the Funeral Payment and aims to reduce funeral poverty in Scotland by providing people who receive certain benefits or tax credits with a payment that can be used to help pay funeral costs, burial or cremation costs, travel costs, and medical costs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.socialsecurity.gov.scot/what-we-do/stakeholder-resources/funeral-support-payment|title=Social Security Scotland|website=Funeral Support Payment|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> Payments have been increased in line with inflation for applications submitted from 1 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.socialsecurity.gov.scot/news/benefit-payments-are-increasing|title=Benefit payments are increasing|last=Social Security Scotland|first=|date=2020-04-01|website=socialsecurity.gov.scot|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Carer\u2019s Allowance Supplement===\nAn extra payment to carers in Scotland who are receiving a full or partial Carer's Allowance payment from the Department for Work and Pensions. Social Security Scotland pays this every six months, in June and December, until Scottish Government plans for a new Carer's Allowance are in place. Each six monthly payment will be \u00a3226.20, uprated annually with inflation. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mygov.scot/carers-allowance-supplement/|title=Carer\u2019s Allowance Supplement|last=Scottish Government|first=|date=2019-06-11|website=mygov.scot|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> From 6 April 2020, Carer's Allowance Supplement will increase to \u00a3230.10 for each payment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.socialsecurity.gov.scot/news/benefit-payments-are-increasing|title=Benefit payments are increasing|last=Social Security Scotland|first=|date=2020-04-01|website=socialsecurity.gov.scot|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Young Carer Grant===\nYoung Carer Grant is a grant for young carers, aged 16 to 18 years old, who care for someone for at least 16 hours a week but do not qualify for Carer's Allowance. The grant provides a payment of \u00a3300 every year to young carers up until the age of 19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/news/more-support-for-young-carers|title=More support for Young Carers|website=gov.scot|access-date=2019-11-10}}</ref> From 1 April 2020, Young Carer Grant will increase from \u00a3300.00 to \u00a3305.10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.socialsecurity.gov.scot/news/benefit-payments-are-increasing|title=Benefit payments are increasing|last=Social Security Scotland|first=|date=2020-04-01|website=socialsecurity.gov.scot|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Job Start Payment===\nA payment intended to help young people aged 16-24 who are returning to work after a period of six months unemployment. It will provide a payment of \u00a3100, or \u00a3250 for those who have children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dgxmvz0tqkndr.cloudfront.net/production/images/general/Building-Better-Benefits-Flyer.pdf|title=Building a better benefits system for Scotland|last=Social Security Scotland|first=|date=2019-02-01|website=Social Security Scotland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> Initially scheduled to launch in March 2020, this payment has been delayed due to the [[COVID-19]] pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/publications/statement-covid-19-update-devolved-benefits|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) - update on devolved benefits: Cabinet Secretary speech|website=gov.scot|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Scottish Child Payment===\nScottish Child Payment is a new payment announced by the Scottish Government in mid-2019 as a means to help reduce the prevalence of childhood poverty in Scotland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jrf.org.uk/blog/scottish-child-payment-will-turn-tide-child-poverty|title=The Scottish Child Payment will turn the tide on child poverty|date=2019-06-28|website=JRF|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> \n\nThe payment was to be introduced early for families with children under six years old, starting in early 2021, with all remaining eligible families with children under 16 years old receiving the payment by the end of 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/policies/social-security/scottish-child-payment|title=Scottish Child Payment|access-date=2019-11-10}}</ref> However, due to the [[COVID-19]] pandemic, the introduction has been postponed, with the Scottish Government aiming to have applications open for families by the end of 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/publications/statement-covid-19-update-devolved-benefits|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) - update on devolved benefits: Cabinet Secretary speech|website=gov.scot|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Disability Assistance===\n\n===Cold Spell Heating Assistance===\n\n===Winter Heating Assistance===\n\n===Employment Injury Assistance===\n\n==Locations==\n\nSocial Security Scotland operates from a Headquarters in [[Dundee]] and a large office on High Street, [[Glasgow]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottishhousingnews.com/article/location-revealed-for-social-security-scotlands-dundee-base|title=Location revealed for Social Security Scotland\u2019s Dundee base|last=News|first=Scottish Housing|website=Scottish Housing News|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\nThe agency also has local level operations in conjunction with local authorities to ensure accessibility throughout Scotland for face-to-face service provision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.gov.scot/social-security/2018/04/27/first-local-jobs-for-social-security-scotland/|title=First local jobs for Social Security Scotland|date=2018-04-27|website=Social Security|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==Budget==\n\nIn 2019\u201320, the Scottish Government budget for Social Security policy totalled at over \u00a3434 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/publications/scottish-budget-2019-20/pages/16/|title=Scottish Budget 2019-2020 - gov.scot|website=www.gov.scot|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==Social Security reserved to the United Kingdom==\n{{See also|Department for Work and Pensions}}\n\nWith the Scotland Act 2016 only devolving some aspects of social security provisions, most services remain reserved to the U.K. Government, administered through the [[Department for Work and Pensions]] based on UK Government policy decisions. These include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/devolution-settlement-scotland|title=Devolution settlement: Scotland|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/browse/benefits|title=Benefits - GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n* [[Universal Credit]] \n* [[Jobseeker's Allowance]]\n* [[Employment Support Allowance]]\n* [[Income Support]]\n* [[Working Tax Credit]]\n* [[Child Tax Credit]]\n* [[Housing Benefit]]\n* [[Child Benefit]]\n* [[Severe Disablement Allowance]]\n* [[Maternity Allowance]]\n* [[Guardian's allowance|Guardian's Allowance]]\n* [[State Pension]]\n* [[Pension Credit]]\n* [[Incapacity Benefit]]\n* [[Vaccine Damage Payment]]\n* [[Widowed Parent's Allowance]]\n* [[Support for Mortgage Interest]]\n* Statuary Payment\n* Bereavement Allowance\n* Bereavement Payment\n* Widowed Payment Allowance\n* Carer's Credit\n* Armed Forces Independence Payment\n* Parents Learning Allowance\n* Blind Person's Allowance\n* National Concessionary Fuel Scheme\n* Warm Home Discount Scheme \n* War Widower Pension\n* Mortgage Interest Run On\n* Diffuse Mesothelioma Payment\n* Disability Premiums\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Executive agencies of the Scottish Government}}\n\n[[Category:Executive agencies of the Scottish Government]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Social security in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 2018]]\n[[Category:Scotland government stubs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox government agency\n|agency_name     = Social Security Scotland<br>T\u00e8arainteachd Sh\u00f2isealta Alba\n|type            = [[Executive agencies of the Scottish Government|Executive Agency]]\n|logo            = Social Security Scotland logo.svg\n|logo_width      =\n|logo_caption    =\n|seal            =\n|seal_width      =\n|seal_caption    =\n|picture         =\n|picture_width   =\n|picture_caption =\n|formed          = 2018\n|preceding1      = [[Department for Work and Pensions]]\n|preceding2      = [[Secretary of State for Work and Pensions]]\n<!-- (etc.) -->\n|dissolved       =\n|superseding     =\n|jurisdiction    = [[Scotland]]\n|headquarters    = [[Dundee]]<br>[[Glasgow]]\n|coordinates     =\n|motto           = Dignity, fairness, respect.\n|employees       =\n|budget          =\n|minister1_name  = [[Shirley-Anne Somerville|Shirley-Anne Somerville MSP]]\n|minister1_pfo   = [[Cabinet Secretary for Social Security and Older People|Cabinet Secretary for Social Security]]\n|minister2_name  =\n|minister2_pfo   =\n<!-- (etc.) -->\n|deputyminister1_name  = [[Christina McKelvie|Christina McKelvie MSP]]\n|deputyminister1_pfo   = [[Minister for Older People and Equalities]]\n|deputyminister2_name  =\n|deputyminister2_pfo   =\n<!-- (etc.) -->\n|chief1_name     = David Wallace\n|chief1_position = Chief Executive\n|website         = {{URL|https://www.socialsecurity.gov.scot/|Social Security Scotland}}\n|footnotes       =\n|map             =\n|map_width       =\n|map_caption     =\n}}\n\n'''Social Security Scotland''' ([[Scottish Gaelic language|Scottish Gaelic]]: ''T\u00e8arainteachd Sh\u00f2isealta Alba'') is an executive agency of the [[Scottish Government]] with responsibility for [[Social security in Scotland|social security]] provision.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-43885731|title=Holyrood approves social security bill|last=BBC|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe [[Scottish Parliament]] was re-established in 1999 with legislative authority over many areas of social policy. However, social security remained a reserved matter of the [[UK Government]] through the [[Department for Work and Pensions]].  The [[Smith Commission]] following the \u2018No\u2019 vote to independence in the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|2014 referendum]] recommended that authority over several areas of social security be transferred to the Scottish Parliament under a revised devolution settlement for Scotland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.parliament.scot/ResearchBriefingsAndFactsheets/S4/SB_15-07_The_Smith_Commission_Welfare_Proposals.pdf|title=The Smith Commission's Welfare Proposals - Scottish Parliament|last=SPICe - Scottish Parliament|first=|date=21 January 2015|website=Scottish Parliament|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis was put into statue through the [[Scotland Act 2016]].\n\n==Legislation==\n{{Main|Social Security (Scotland) Act 2018}}\n\nWith the Scotland Act 2016 transferring authority over some elements of social security, the Scottish Government introduced the Social Security (Scotland) Bill.  This Bill introduced a different approach to administering social security in Scotland compared to the approach of the United Kingdom.  The Bill set out 8 principles of social security, putting into statute that social security is a human right, it is to be delivered as a public service and that it is to contribute to the reducing of poverty and provide dignity and respect to Scottish citizens.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-43885731|title=Holyrood approves social security bill|date=2018-04-25|access-date=2019-10-04|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe Bill sets out the need for a Scottish social security charter, which sets out the expectations of Scottish Ministers when developing social security policy, the expectations of Social Security Scotland when administering policies, and the expectations on individuals who are receiving assistance from Social Security Scotland.\n\nThe Bill established the Scottish Commission on Social Security, which is a corporate body independent of the Scottish Government.  The Commission\u2019s purpose is to scrutinise Scottish Government policy decisions and to ensure that the Scottish Government and Social Security Scotland are fulfilling the legal requirements under the Bill. \n\nThis Bill was passed on 25 April 2018 and received Royal Assent on 1 June 2018 as the [[Social Security (Scotland) Act 2018]]. It is the first Scotland wide social security agency in the nation's history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2018/9/enacted/data.htm|title=Social Security (Scotland) Act 2018|website=www.legislation.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==Ministers==\n\nThe Minister of the Scottish Government with responsibility for Social Security Scotland is the [[Cabinet Secretary for Social Security and Older People]], supported by the [[Minister for Older People and Equalities]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/about/who-runs-government/cabinet-and-ministers/|title=Cabinet and ministers - gov.scot|website=www.gov.scot|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"  cellpadding=\"6\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 0 0 0 1em; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaaaaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; \" \n|colspan=\"8\"|\n=== Minister for Social Security===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|[[Jeane Freeman]]\n| [[File:JeaneFreemanMSP.jpg|60px]]\n| 18 May 2016\n| 26 June 2018\n|[[Scottish National Party]]\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|[[Nicola Sturgeon]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"8\"|\n=== Cabinet Secretary for Social Security and Older People ===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|[[Shirley-Anne Somerville]]\n| [[File:Minister for Further Education, Higher Education and Science, Shirley Anne Sommerville.png|60px]]\n| 26 June 2018\n| ''incumbent''\n|[[Scottish National Party]]\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|[[Nicola Sturgeon]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Benefits==\n\n===Best Start Grant===\n[[Best Start Grant]] replaces the Sure Start Maternity Grant and is made up of three payments: Pregnancy and Baby Payment, Early Learning Payment, and School Age Payment. Best Start Foods is also under the Best Start Grant umbrella. The benefits are aimed at providing parents or carers who receive certain benefits or tax credits with extra financial support during key stages of a child's life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/policies/social-security/best-start-grant/|title=Social security: Best Start Grant - gov.scot|website=www.gov.scot|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n===Funeral Support Payment===\n[[Funeral Support Payment]] replaces the Funeral Payment and aims to reduce funeral poverty in Scotland by providing people who receive certain benefits or tax credits with a payment that can be used to help pay funeral costs, burial or cremation costs, travel costs, and medical costs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.socialsecurity.gov.scot/what-we-do/stakeholder-resources/funeral-support-payment|title=Social Security Scotland|website=Funeral Support Payment|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> Payments have been increased in line with inflation for applications submitted from 1 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.socialsecurity.gov.scot/news/benefit-payments-are-increasing|title=Benefit payments are increasing|last=Social Security Scotland|first=|date=2020-04-01|website=socialsecurity.gov.scot|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Carer\u2019s Allowance Supplement===\nAn extra payment to carers in Scotland who are receiving a full or partial Carer\u2019s Allowance payment from the Department for Work and Pensions. Social Security Scotland pays this every six months, in June and December, until Scottish Government plans for a new Carer\u2019s Allowance are in place. Each six monthly payment will be \u00a3226.20, uprated annually with inflation. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mygov.scot/carers-allowance-supplement/|title=Carer\u2019s Allowance Supplement|last=Scottish Government|first=|date=2019-06-11|website=mygov.scot|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> From 6 April 2020, Carer's Allowance Supplement will increase to \u00a3230.10 for each payment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.socialsecurity.gov.scot/news/benefit-payments-are-increasing|title=Benefit payments are increasing|last=Social Security Scotland|first=|date=2020-04-01|website=socialsecurity.gov.scot|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Young Carer Grant===\nYoung Carer Grant is a grant for young carers, aged 16 to 18 years old, who care for someone for at least 16 hours a week but do not qualify for Carer's Allowance. The grant provides a payment of \u00a3300 every year to young carers up until the age of 19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/news/more-support-for-young-carers|title=More support for Young Carers|website=gov.scot|access-date=2019-11-10}}</ref> From 1 April 2020, Young Carer Grant will increase from \u00a3300.00 to \u00a3305.10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.socialsecurity.gov.scot/news/benefit-payments-are-increasing|title=Benefit payments are increasing|last=Social Security Scotland|first=|date=2020-04-01|website=socialsecurity.gov.scot|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Job Start Payment===\nA payment intended to help young people aged 16-24 who are returning to work after a period of six months unemployment. It will provide a payment of \u00a3100, or \u00a3250 for those who have children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dgxmvz0tqkndr.cloudfront.net/production/images/general/Building-Better-Benefits-Flyer.pdf|title=Building a better benefits system for Scotland|last=Social Security Scotland|first=|date=2019-02-01|website=Social Security Scotland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> Initially scheduled to launch in March 2020, this payment has been delayed due to the [[COVID-19]] pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/publications/statement-covid-19-update-devolved-benefits|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) - update on devolved benefits: Cabinet Secretary speech|website=gov.scot|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Scottish Child Payment===\nScottish Child Payment is a new payment announced by the Scottish Government in mid-2019 as a means to help reduce the prevalence of childhood poverty in Scotland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jrf.org.uk/blog/scottish-child-payment-will-turn-tide-child-poverty|title=The Scottish Child Payment will turn the tide on child poverty|date=2019-06-28|website=JRF|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> \n\nThe payment was to be introduced early for families with children under six years old, starting in early 2021, with all remaining eligible families with children under 16 years old receiving the payment by the end of 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/policies/social-security/scottish-child-payment|title=Scottish Child Payment|access-date=2019-11-10}}</ref> However, due to the [[COVID-19]] pandemic, the introduction has been postponed, with the Scottish Government aiming to have applications open for families by the end of 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/publications/statement-covid-19-update-devolved-benefits|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) - update on devolved benefits: Cabinet Secretary speech|website=gov.scot|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Disability Assistance===\n\n===Cold Spell Heating Assistance===\n\n===Winter Heating Assistance===\n\n===Employment Injury Assistance===\n\n==Locations==\n\nSocial Security Scotland operates from a Headquarters in [[Dundee]] and a large office on High Street, [[Glasgow]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottishhousingnews.com/article/location-revealed-for-social-security-scotlands-dundee-base|title=Location revealed for Social Security Scotland\u2019s Dundee base|last=News|first=Scottish Housing|website=Scottish Housing News|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\nThe agency also has local level operations in conjunction with local authorities to ensure accessibility throughout Scotland for face-to-face service provision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.gov.scot/social-security/2018/04/27/first-local-jobs-for-social-security-scotland/|title=First local jobs for Social Security Scotland|date=2018-04-27|website=Social Security|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==Budget==\n\nIn 2019-20, the Scottish Government budget for Social Security policy totalled at over \u00a3434 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/publications/scottish-budget-2019-20/pages/16/|title=Scottish Budget 2019-2020 - gov.scot|website=www.gov.scot|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==Social Security reserved to the United Kingdom==\n{{See also|Department for Work and Pensions}}\n\nWith the Scotland Act 2016 only devolving some aspects of social security provisions, most services remain reserved to the U.K. Government, administered through the [[Department for Work and Pensions]] based on UK Government policy decisions. These include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/devolution-settlement-scotland|title=Devolution settlement: Scotland|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/browse/benefits|title=Benefits - GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n* [[Universal Credit]] \n* [[Jobseeker's Allowance]]\n* [[Employment Support Allowance]]\n* [[Income Support]]\n* [[Working Tax Credit]]\n* [[Child Tax Credit]]\n* [[Housing Benefit]]\n* [[Child Benefit]]\n* [[Severe Disablement Allowance]]\n* [[Maternity Allowance]]\n* [[Guardian's allowance|Guardian\u2019s Allowance]]\n* [[State Pension]]\n* [[Pension Credit]]\n* [[Incapacity Benefit]]\n* [[Vaccine Damage Payment]]\n* [[Widowed Parent's Allowance]]\n* [[Support for Mortgage Interest]]\n* Statuary Payment\n* Bereavement Allowance\n* Bereavement Payment\n* Widowed Payment Allowance\n* Carer's Credit\n* Armed Forces Independence Payment\n* Parents Learning Allowance\n* Blind Person's Allowance\n* National Concessionary Fuel Scheme\n* Warm Home Discount Scheme \n* War Widower Pension\n* Mortgage Interest Run On\n* Diffuse Mesothelioma Payment\n* Disability Premiums\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Executive agencies of the Scottish Government}}\n\n[[Category:Executive agencies of the Scottish Government]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Social security in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 2018]]\n[[Category:Scotland government stubs]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "