{"title_page": "Stingray (1964 TV series)", "text_new": "{{Short description|British children' Supermarionation television series}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Stingray\n| image                = Stingray title.jpg\n| genre                = [[Children's television series|Children's]] [[Science fiction on television|science fiction]]<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Evans|first1=Jeff|author1-link=Jeff Evans|title=The Penguin TV Companion|series=Penguin Reference|year=2006|origyear=2001|edition=3rd|publisher=[[Penguin Books]]|location=London, UK|isbn=978-0-141-02424-0|page=786}}</ref>\n| creator              = {{Nowrap|[[Gerry Anderson|Gerry]] and [[Sylvia Anderson]]}}\n| writer               = {{ubl |Gerry and Sylvia Anderson |[[Alan Fennell]] |[[Dennis Spooner]]}}\n| director             = {{ubl |[[David Elliott (director)|David Elliott]] |John Kelly |[[Alan Pattillo]] |[[Desmond Saunders]]}}\n| voices               = {{ubl |[[Ray Barrett]] |[[Robert Easton (actor)|Robert Easton]] |[[David Graham (actor)|David Graham]] |[[Don Mason (actor)|Don Mason]] |[[Lois Maxwell]] |Sylvia Anderson }}\n| opentheme            = \"Stingray\"\n| endtheme             = \"Aqua Marina\"\n| composer             = [[Barry Gray]]\n| country              = United Kingdom\n| language             = English\n| num_series           = 1\n| num_episodes         = 39\n| list_episodes        = #Episodes\n| producer             = Gerry Anderson\n| cinematography       = [[John Read (producer)|John Read]]\n| editor               = {{ubl ||[[David Lane (director)|David Lane]] |Harry MacDonald |Eric Pask}}\n| runtime              = 25 minutes\n| company              = [[AP Films]]\n| distributor          = [[ITC Entertainment]]\n| network              = [[Associated Television|ATV]]\n| picture_format       = [[35mm movie film|35 mm]] ([[Eastmancolor]])<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\">Bentley 2008, p.&nbsp;79.</ref>\n| audio_format         = [[Monaural|Mono]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|df=yes|1964|10|4}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|df=yes|1965|6|27}}\n| preceded_by          = ''[[Fireball XL5]]''\n| followed_by          = ''[[Thunderbirds (TV series)|Thunderbirds]]''\n| website              = hide\n}}\n\n'''''Stingray''''' is a British children's [[Science fiction on television|science-fiction television series]] created by [[Gerry Anderson|Gerry]] and [[Sylvia Anderson]] and produced by [[AP Films]] (APF) for [[ITC Entertainment]]. Filmed in 1963 using a combination of electronic [[marionette]] puppetry and [[scale model]] special effects, it was APF's sixth puppet series and the third to be produced under the banner of \"[[Supermarionation]]\". It debuted on British television in October 1964.\n\nSet in the [[2060s]], the series follows the exploits of the World Aquanaut Security Patrol (WASP), a military organisation responsible for policing the Earth's oceans. The WASP's top vessel is ''Stingray'', a combat submarine piloted by the daring Captain Troy Tempest, aided by his loyal navigator, Lieutenant \"Phones\" Sheridan, and Marina, a young woman from under the sea. ''Stingray''{{'}}s adventures bring it into contact with various underwater civilisations, some friendly and others hostile, as well as mysterious natural phenomena.\n\nIn preparation for the series, APF acquired new, larger studios that it would continue to occupy for the remainder of the 1960s. Filmed at a cost of approximately \u00a31&nbsp;million,<ref name=\"O'Brien80\">O'Brien, p.&nbsp;80.</ref> ''Stingray'' was the first British TV series to be made entirely in colour,<ref name=\"Bentley2008,80\">Bentley 2008, p.&nbsp;80.</ref><ref>La Rivi\u00e8re, p.&nbsp;96.</ref> a move intended to increase its appeal to the lucrative American market.<ref name=\"Rogers68\">Rogers et al., p.&nbsp;68.</ref><ref name=\"Peel240\">Peel, p.&nbsp;240.</ref><ref name=\"SangsterCondon\"/> The underwater sequences were filmed \"dry\" by shooting the sets through thin aquaria, while surface shots were filmed on water tanks incorporating lowered back walls to create artificial horizons. ''Stingray'' was the first Supermarionation series whose puppet characters were provided with interchangeable heads enabling them to show a variety of facial expressions.\n\n''Stingray''{{'}}s 39 half-hour episodes were originally broadcast on [[Associated Television]] in the United Kingdom and in [[Broadcast syndication|syndication]] in North America. The series has drawn a largely positive response from commentators, some of whom have compared its premise to the [[Cold War]].\n\n==Premise==\n''Stingray'', a [[Nuclear submarine|nuclear-powered]] combat [[submarine]], is the [[flagship]] of the World Aquanaut Security Patrol (WASP), a branch of the World Security Patrol (WSP) responsible for policing the Earth's oceans in the mid-[[2060s]].<ref group=\"Note\">Sources give the year as 2064 (Archer and Hearn, p.&nbsp;88; Bentley 2001, p.&nbsp;12) or 2065 (Sellers, p.&nbsp;88). The episode \"The Lighthouse Dwellers\" is set in 2065 (La Rivi\u00e8re, p.&nbsp;103). The episode \"Eastern Eclipse\" is set 12 months after \"Star of the East\" (Bentley 2008, p.&nbsp;92).</ref> Armed with \"sting missile\" [[torpedo]]es, it can travel at up to {{Convert|600|kn|kph mph}} underwater<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/><ref name=\"Sellers90\">Sellers, p.&nbsp;90.</ref> and reach depths of over {{Convert|36000|ft|km mi}}.\n\nThe WASP is based in the self-contained city of Marineville, located several miles inland somewhere on the [[West Coast of North America]].<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/><ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re2013\">{{Cite magazine|magazine=[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]|title=Time Machine: ''Stingray''|last1=La Rivi\u00e8re|first1=Stephen|editor1-last=Bradley|editor1-first=David|pages=76\u201377|date=May 2013|issue=233|publisher=[[Future Publishing]]|location=Bath, UK|issn=1749-6969|oclc=813632043}}</ref> It is connected to the [[Pacific Ocean]] via a tunnel leading to an \"ocean door\", through which ''Stingray'' is launched. [[General quarters]] alerts are sounded by rapid drum beats played over the base's [[public address]] system. In emergency situations, the entire base is lowered into vast underground bunkers on giant hydraulic jacks while [[fighter aircraft]] and interceptor missiles are launched to counter threats. WASP personnel acknowledge commands with the phrase \"P.W.O.R.\" \u2013 short for \"Proceeding With Orders Received\".\n\n''Stingray'' is piloted by the square-jawed Captain Troy Tempest. He is paired with [[American South|Southern]] navigator Lieutenant George Lee Sheridan, nicknamed \"Phones\" for his side role as ''Stingray''{{'}}s [[hydrophone]] operator. Troy and Phones board ''Stingray'' by sitting on twin seats in Marineville's stand-by lounge, which are lowered into the submarine via injector tubes and then clamped into place. They answer to their \"[[Wheelchair|hoverchair]]\"-bound Commander Sam Shore, whose daughter, Lieutenant Atlanta Shore, works in the Marineville control tower and is enamoured of Troy.\n\nThe series begins with the WASP's discovery that the ocean floor is home to many advanced civilisations. Prominent among these is the undersea city of Titanica, ruled by King Titan. A despot, Titan commands the Aquaphibians who possess a fleet of lethal submersibles called \"Mechanical Fish\".<ref group=\"Note\">In [[tie-in]] media, they are called \"Terror Fish\" (Bentley 2008, p.&nbsp;355).</ref> In the first episode, ''Stingray'' is attacked by Titan's forces and Troy and Phones are captured. They are rescued by Titan's slave, Marina, a [[Muteness|mute]] young woman from the undersea city of Pacifica who can breathe underwater.\n\nTroy and Phones take Marina to Marineville, where she becomes a permanent member of the ''Stingray'' crew. Troy becomes infatuated with her, making Atlanta jealous. Meanwhile, Titan, furious at Marina's betrayal, vows revenge on \"terraineans\" (land people) in general and Troy and the WASP in particular.\n\nMany later episodes revolve around Titan's unsuccessful schemes to destroy ''Stingray'' and Marineville, which usually fail due to the incompetence of Surface Agent X-2-Zero, his spy on land. X-2-Zero is based on the Pacific island of Lemoy, where he lives in an outwardly  dilapidated house whose walls conceal banks of highly sophisticated surveillance and tracking equipment. Other episodes feature encounters with other races living under the sea or within the Earth (some friendly and others hostile), as well as investigation of natural phenomena. The final episode is a [[clip show]] in which Troy is named \"Aquanaut of the Year\" and a selection of ''Stingray''{{'}}s adventures are recalled as [[Flashback (narrative)|flashbacks]].\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table\n|overall=\n|title=\n|director=\n|writer=\n|airdate=\n|prodcode=\n|airdateT=Original air date ([[ATV London]])\n|airdateR=<ref name=\"Bentley2008,81-93\">Bentley 2008, pp.&nbsp;81\u201393.</ref>\n|prodcodeR=<ref name=\"Bentley2008,81-93\"/>\n|episodes=\n\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=1\n|Title=Stingray\n|RTitle=<ref group=\"Note\">The first episode has no on-screen title but is referred to as \"Stingray\" in documentation by distributor [[ITC Entertainment]] (Archer and Hearn, p.&nbsp;97). It is also known as \"Stingray (The Pilot)\" or simply \"The Pilot\" (Rogers et al., p.&nbsp;44). It was not devised as a true [[Television pilot|pilot]] as [[Lew Grade]], the Andersons' financial backer, had already approved the series format (Fryer 2016, p.&nbsp;82). In his biography, Gerry Anderson said that the first episodes of series that he produced were called \"pilots\" for the sake of convenience (Archer and Hearn, p.&nbsp;88).</ref>\n|DirectedBy=[[Alan Pattillo]]\n|WrittenBy=[[Gerry Anderson|Gerry]] and [[Sylvia Anderson]]\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1964|10|4|df=y}}\n|ProdCode=1\n|ShortSummary=When a World Navy submarine is mysteriously destroyed, Troy and Phones are assigned to investigate. However, they are captured by the Aquaphibians and sentenced to life imprisonment in the undersea penal complex of Aquatraz by Titan of Titanica.\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=2\n|Title=Emergency Marineville\n|DirectedBy=John Kelly\n|WrittenBy=[[Alan Fennell]]\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1964|10|11|df=y}}\n|ProdCode=11\n|ShortSummary=A series of unsuccessful missile attacks against Marineville leads to the ''Stingray'' crew needing to sabotage the culprits' attempt to evade WASP's interceptor rockets.\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=3\n|Title=[[The Ghost Ship (Stingray)|The Ghost Ship]]\n|DirectedBy=[[Desmond Saunders]]\n|WrittenBy=Alan Fennell\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1964|10|18|df=y}}\n|ProdCode=8\n|ShortSummary=Commander Shore and Phones are held hostage by a plundering villain. Troy tries to find a way to rescue to his friends even it means disobeying Commander Shore's orders.\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=4\n|Title=Subterranean Sea\n|DirectedBy=Desmond Saunders\n|WrittenBy=Alan Fennell\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1964|10|25|df=y}}\n|ProdCode=12\n|ShortSummary=The ''Stingray'' crew brave the perils of a newly discovered underground sea when their vacation leave is cancelled.\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=5\n|Title=Loch Ness Monster\n|DirectedBy=Alan Pattillo\n|WrittenBy=[[Dennis Spooner]]\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1964|11|1|df=y}}\n|ProdCode=13\n|ShortSummary=Troy, Phones and Atlanta are sent to Scotland to solve the mystery of [[Loch Ness Monster|Nessie]] once and for all.\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=6\n|Title=Set Sail for Adventure\n|DirectedBy=[[David Elliott (director)|David Elliott]]\n|WrittenBy=Dennis Spooner\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1964|11|8|df=y}}\n|ProdCode=30\n|ShortSummary=A storm injures an admiral on his sailing vessel, causing him to lose his memory and turn his cannons on ''Stingray''.\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|