-minute condensed reconstruction of the 1963 feature presentation, excluding the material from \"Raptures of the Deep\". Created in collaboration with [[BBC Wales]]. First broadcast as part of \"Gerry Anderson Night\" on [[BBC Four]] on 2 January 2008.<ref name=\"Bentley2008,94\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/schedules/p00fzl6b/2008/01/02|title=BBC Four \u2013 Schedules, Wednesday 2 January 2008|work=[[BBC Online]]|publisher=BBC|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180602164646/https://www.bbc.co.uk/schedules/p00fzl6b/2008/01/02|archive-date=2 June 2018|url-status=live|access-date=24 March 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n\n===Compilation films===\nBetween 1980 and 1981, two [[compilation film]]s were produced, each made up of re-edited versions of four of the original episodes. These films were produced specifically for the American market and aired in the United States as part of an [[ITC Entertainment]] package titled \"Super Space Theater\"; other Supermarionation series were given similar treatments. One of the ''Stingray'' films, ''Invaders from the Deep'', was broadcast as the first episode of movie-mocking TV series ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'' in November 1988.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Beaulieu |first1=Trace |last2=Chaplin |first2=Paul |last3=Mallon |first3=Jim |last4=Murphy |first4=Kevin |last5=Nelson |first5=Michael J. |last6=Pehl |first6=Mary Jo |title=The ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'' Amazing Colossal Episode Guide |date=May 1996 |publisher=[[Bantam Books]] |isbn=978-0553377835|page=40}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%; text-align:center\"\n|- \n! Title\n! Compilation of\n! Released\n|-\n| ''The Incredible Voyage of Stingray''\n| \"Stingray\", \"Plant of Doom\", \"Count Down\" and \"The Master Plan\"\n| 1980\n|-\n| ''Invaders from the Deep''\n| \"Hostages of the Deep\", \"Emergency Marineville\", \"The Big Gun\" and \"Deep Heat\"\n| 1981\n|}\n\n==Characters==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; float: right; margin-right: 0; margin-left: 1em\"\n|+ Voice cast\n|- \n! Actor\n! Main characters voiced\n|-\n| [[Ray Barrett]] || Commander Shore<br />Titan<br />Sub-Lieutenant Fisher\n|-\n| [[Robert Easton (actor)|Robert Easton]] || Phones<br />Surface Agent X-2-Zero<br />Aquaphibians\n|-\n| [[David Graham (actor)|David Graham]] || Oink<br />\"Doc\"<br />Admiral Denver<br />Aquaphibians\n|-\n| [[Don Mason (actor)|Don Mason]] || Troy Tempest\n|-\n| [[Lois Maxwell]] || Atlanta\n|-\n| [[Sylvia Anderson]] || Marina<ref group=\"Note\" name=\"Marina\">Marina is voiced by [[Sylvia Anderson]] on two occasions: the TV episode \"Raptures of the Deep\" and the audio play \"Marina Speaks\" (Bentley 2008, p.&nbsp;86). In \"Raptures of the Deep\", Troy experiences a hallucination in which Marina communicates with him [[telepathically]]. \"Marina Speaks\" reveals that Marina is actually not mute at all, but unwilling to speak due to a curse that Titan placed on her people \u2013 should any one of them speak, another will die (Sangster and Condon, p.&nbsp;722).</ref>\n|-\n| [[Gary Miller (singer)|Gary Miller]] || Troy Tempest (singing voice)\n|}\n\n===WASP personnel===\n* '''Captain Troy Tempest''': pilot of the WASP's main submarine, ''Stingray''.\n* '''\"Phones\"''': a WASP lieutenant, ''Stingray''{{'}}s navigator and hydrophone operator, and Troy's best friend. His real name, George Lee Sheridan, is mentioned in the series' publicity material but not spoken on-screen.\n* '''Marina''': a young woman from under the sea who joins the ''Stingray'' crew, and Troy's primary love interest. She is the former slave of King Titan of Titanica. Daughter of Aphony, ruler of the undersea city of Pacifica, she is mute like all other Pacificans.\n* '''Lieutenant Atlanta Shore''': assistant controller in Marineville Tower and rival of Marina for Troy's affections.\n* '''Commander Samuel Shore''': head of Marineville and father of Atlanta. He cannot walk and is confined to a hoverchair. The reason for his disability is revealed in the episode \"The Ghost of the Sea\": as a security agent for a deep-sea mining platform, he was seriously injured when a hostile submersible attacked the facility and damaged his patrol craft.\n* '''Sub-Lieutenant John Horatio Fisher''': an eager, young WASP lieutenant who is junior assistant controller in Marineville Tower. In the episode \"Rescue from the Skies\" he is seen training to be an aquanaut.\n\n===Villains===\n* '''King Titan of Titanica''': the tyrannical ruler of the undersea city of Titanica and Marina's former master.\n* '''Surface Agent X-2-Zero''': Titan's main agent on land.\n* '''Aquaphibians''': an undersea warrior race who serve as Titan's minions.\n\n===Recurring characters===\n* '''Oink''': a seal pup who joins the ''Stingray'' crew as Marina's pet after saving them from a bomb in the episode \"Sea of Oil\".\n* '''\"Doc\"''': Marineville's doctor.\n* '''Admiral Jack Denver''': the president of the WASP underwater research division. He went to college with Commander Shore and enjoys debating with him.\n* '''WSP Commanders''': three World Security Patrol commanders, based at WSP Headquarters in [[Washington, D.C.]], who appear in various episodes to brief Commander Shore.\n\n==Production==\nIn late 1962, as production on ''[[Fireball XL5]]'' drew to a close, [[Gerry Anderson]] decided that an underwater series was the next logical step for production company [[AP Films]] (APF): \"We had been on land and in space, so where could we go next? One possibility was underwater.\"<ref name=\"ArcherHearn88\">Archer and Hearn, p.&nbsp;88.</ref> He was inspired by childhood memories of [[U-boat]]s in the [[Second World War]], as well as by the mysteries of the ocean: \"I was ... fascinated by trenches in the ocean that are as deep as mountains are high. There are features that man has never seen and pressures that are almost impossible to withstand. I began to wonder if there were areas of the Earth which had been little explored and felt justified in writing some wacky stuff.\"<ref name=\"ArcherHearn89\">Archer and Hearn, p.&nbsp;89.</ref>\n\nAPF's financer [[Lew Grade]], who had bought the company after the success of ''Fireball XL5'',<ref>Bentley 2001, pp.&nbsp;11\u201312.</ref> approved the concept and commissioned 26 episodes.<ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re102\">La Rivi\u00e8re, p.&nbsp;102.</ref> Anderson named the new series \"Stingray\" partly from a belief that [[stingray]]s are dangerous animals (in reality, they are docile), but also because it \"seemed an exciting title.\"<ref name=\"ArcherHearn89\"/>\n\n===Filming===\nIn preparation for the new series, APF, then based on the [[Slough Trading Estate]]'s Ipswich Road, moved to a larger site on the nearby Stirling Road at a cost of \u00a375,000<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/><ref name=\"ArcherHearn90\">Archer and Hearn, p.&nbsp;90.</ref> (approximately \u00a3{{Inflation|UK|0.075|1963|r=2}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation-year|UK}}). The new studios, built inside a converted factory unit, contained three {{Convert|40 x 45|ft|m|adj=on}} shooting stages:<ref name=\"ArcherHearn90\"/> two for puppet filming and one for [[special effects]].<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/> This arrangement allowed two episodes to be filmed simultaneously by separate crews.<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/>\n\nProduction began in spring or June<ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re2013\"/> 1963 and the series was completed in ten months.<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/> Each episode required an average of 11 days' puppet filming and 5.5 days effects shooting.<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/> The total cost of the production was approximately \u00a31&nbsp;million<ref name=\"O'Brien80\"/><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Encyclopaedia of Cult Children's TV|last1=Lewis|first1=Richard|year=2002|origyear=2001|publisher=[[Allison & Busby]]|location=London, UK|isbn=9780749005290|page=286}}</ref> (approximately \u00a3{{Inflation|UK|1|1963|r=2}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation-year|UK}}).\n\nThe budget per episode was \u00a320,000 (approximately \u00a3{{Inflation|UK|0.020|1963|r=2}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation-year|UK}}), which enabled APF, whose earlier productions had been in [[black and white]], to film in [[Eastmancolor]].<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/><ref group=\"Note\">The [[opening credits]] refer to the colour process as \"Videcolor\".</ref> Though ''Stingray'' was to premiere in black and white in its country of origin, the switch to colour filming was intended to increase the series' chances of being bought by a network in the US, where colour TV broadcasts were already common.<ref name=\"Rogers68\"/><ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re2013\"/><ref name=\"SAnderson\">{{Cite magazine|magazine=Action TV|issue=4|date=May 2001|publisher=The Shipley Print Company|location=Leeds, UK|title=Lady Penelope Speaks: Interview with Sylvia Anderson|last1=Lewis|first1=Jim|editor1-last=Richardson|editor1-first=Michael|pages=7\u201314}}</ref> Sets were re-painted after [[NBC]] supplied APF with a list of colours believed to cause problems such as flaring or bleeding; according to Anderson, this was unnecessary because when filmed in Eastmancolour, a set \"would appear on screen exactly as you had painted it.\"<ref name=\"ArcherHearn91\">Archer and Hearn, p.&nbsp;91.</ref> Some colours were avoided as they did not come out well in black and white,<ref>Meddings, pp.&nbsp;33\u201334.</ref> and models and sets were painted differently to ensure that they did not blend into each other.<ref name=\"Holliss\">{{Cite magazine|magazine=[[Animato!]]|issue=40|date=Winter-Spring 1999|publisher=Duquette, Patrick|location=Monson, Massachusetts|editor1-last=Duquette|editor1-first=Patrick|last1=Holliss|first1=Richard|title=The Worlds of Gerry Anderson \u2013 Part One: From ''The Adventures of Twizzle'' to ''Thunderbirds''|issn=1042-539X|oclc=19081197|pages=44\u201352}}</ref> During the production of ''Stingray'', APF became the UK's largest [[colour film]] consumer.<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/>\n\nGrade later extended his commission to 39 episodes.<ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re102\"/> As shooting on the final 13 episodes commenced, voice actors [[Don Mason (actor)|Don Mason]] and [[Robert Easton (actor)|Robert Easton]], who had understood that all members of the cast were on equal pay, learnt that they were actually earning less than their co-star [[David Graham (actor)|David Graham]].<ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re102\"/> They did not commit to the remaining episodes until their fees had been re-negotiated.<ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re102\"/>\n\nIn a first for a Supermarionation series, ''Stingray'' features a Christmas-themed episode (\"A Christmas to Remember\") and a [[clip show]] series finale, \"Aquanaut of the Year\". The latter incorporates elements from ''[[This Is Your Life]]'', for which APF was required to obtain the approval of the programme's creator, [[Ralph Edwards]]. The negotiations with Edwards were slow to progress, so work commenced on an alternative finale in which the characters of Commander Shore and Admiral Denver use a film projector to view recordings of some of ''Stingray''{{'}}s past missions. However, production on this episode was halted when Edwards finally gave APF permission to proceed with \"Aquanaut of the Year\".<ref name=\"ArcherHearn99\">Archer and Hearn, p.&nbsp;99.</ref> The linking material from the abandoned episode was re-discovered in 2000 or 2001 and subsequently included on ''Stingray'' DVD releases.<ref name=\"Bentley2008,94\"/><ref name=\"ArcherHearn100\">Archer and Hearn, p.&nbsp;100.</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|title=News: ''Stingray'' and ''Scarlet''|journal=[[TV Zone]]|last1=May|first1=Dominic|issue=138|date=May 2001|publication-date=April 2001|publisher=[[Visual Imagination]]|location=London, UK|issn=0957-3844|oclc=226121852|page=6}}</ref> Several years later, it was combined with footage from \"Stingray\", \"An Echo of Danger\", and \"Emergency Marineville\" to create a new 29-minute clip show titled \"The Reunion Party\", which was first broadcast in 2008.<ref name=\"Bentley2008,94\"/>\n\n===Characters and puppets===\nSylvia Anderson, who had voiced the regular characters of Jimmy Gibson in ''[[Supercar (TV series)|Supercar]]'' and Dr Venus in ''Fireball XL5'', wrote in her 2007 autobiography that she devised Marina as mute because she wanted to take a break from voice acting and \"concentrate on the scripts and characters\".<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Anderson|first1=Sylvia|author1-link=Sylvia Anderson|title=Sylvia Anderson: My Fab Years!|year=2007|publisher=[[Hermes Press]]|location=Neshannock, Pennsylvania|isbn = 978-1-932563-91-7|page=21}}</ref> Her vocal contributions to ''Stingray'' were limited to uncredited guest roles in the episodes \"Raptures of the Deep\" (as Marina)<ref group=\"Note\" name=\"Marina\"/> and \"A Christmas to Remember\".<ref>Bentley 2008, p.&nbsp;86.</ref><ref>Bentley 2008, p.&nbsp;93.</ref>\n\nGerry Anderson said that the character of Phones was inspired by the mannerisms of a [[sound engineer]] with whom he had once worked: \"He spent so long with his headphones plugged in to various bits of equipment that he used to leave them on all the time, earning himself the nickname 'Phones'.\"<ref name=\"ArcherHearn89\"/> Voice actor Robert Easton based the character's [[Southern American]] tones on his performance in the 1961 film ''[[Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea]]'', in which he had played a Southern radio operator called Sparks.<ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re101\"/> The voice of Surface Agent X-2-Zero was Easton's impression of actor [[Peter Lorre]], who had appeared in the same film.<ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re101\"/>\n\nThe design of the Aquaphibians was based on a villainous alien featured in the ''Fireball XL5'' episode \"XL5 to H<sub>2</sub>O\".<ref>Bentley 2008, p.&nbsp;67.</ref><ref>Hearn, p.&nbsp;39.</ref> The characters were voiced by [[Robert Easton (actor)|Robert Easton]] and [[David Graham (actor)|David Graham]] aided by a looped tape recording of bubbling water.<ref name=\"Sellers90\"/>\n\nThe process of designing and making the puppets took four months and each of the main characters was sculpted in duplicate to allow episodes to be filmed in pairs.<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/><ref name=\"ArcherHearn94\"/> The likenesses of some of the puppets were inspired by real-life actors. Troy Tempest was modelled on [[James Garner]];<ref name=\"SangsterCondon\"/><ref name=\"SAnderson\"/><ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re98\"/><ref name=\"Peel19\">Peel, p.&nbsp;19.</ref><ref>Sellers, p.&nbsp;89.</ref> according to Gerry Anderson, this was at his own suggestion because the sculptors were struggling with his original brief.<ref>Archer and Hearn, p.&nbsp;112.</ref> Titan was based on a young [[Laurence Olivier]]<ref name=\"ArcherHearn94\"/> and Surface Agent X-2-Zero on either [[Claude Rains]]<ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re98\">La Rivi\u00e8re, p.&nbsp;98.</ref><ref name=\"Rogers75\">Rogers et al., p.&nbsp;75.</ref> or Peter Lorre.<ref name=\"ArcherHearn94\"/> Atlanta Shore has been likened to [[Lois Maxwell]] (who voiced the character)<ref name=\"SangsterCondon\"/><ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re98\"/><ref name=\"Peel19\"/><ref>{{Cite magazine|magazine=[[Starlog]]|volume=3|issue=16|date=September 1978|publisher=O'Quinn Studios|location=New York City, New York|editor1-last=Zimmerman|editor1-first=Howard|last1=Hirsch|first1=David|last2=Hutchison|first2=David|title=The Magical Techniques of Movie & TV SFX \u2013 Part XI: Supermarionation|page=63}}</ref> and Marina to both [[Brigitte Bardot]]<ref name=\"SangsterCondon\"/><ref name=\"Rogers53\">Rogers et al., p.&nbsp;53.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.starburstmagazine.com/reviews/stingray-the-complete-colletion|title=''Stingray: The Complete Collection''|work=[[Starburst (magazine)|starburstmagazine.com]]|last1=Watson|first1=Nigel|date=28 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180530004830/https://www.starburstmagazine.com/reviews/stingray-the-complete-colletion\n|archive-date=30 May 2018|url-status=live|access-date=24 March 2019}}</ref> and [[Ursula Andress]].<ref name=\"ArcherHearn94\"/><ref>Sellers, pp.&nbsp;89\u201390.</ref>\n\n''Stingray'' was the first Supermarionation series to feature puppets with glass eyes and poseable hands for greater realism.<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/><ref name=\"SangsterCondon\"/><ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re98\"/> To make the puppets' eyes sparkle in a lifelike way, they were polished with [[silicon]] and illuminated using a special \"eye light\" (a small lamp).<ref>{{Cite book |title = Thunderbirds \u2013 A Complete Guide to the Classic Series | chapter = Setting the Scene | last1 = Hearn | first1 = Marcus | editor1-last = Hearn | editor1-first = Marcus | publisher = [[Panini UK]] | location = Tunbridge Wells, UK | date = September 2015 | isbn = 978-1-84653-212-2 | page = 63}}</ref> A further innovation was the creation of alternative puppet heads to allow characters to display emotions: as well as their \"normal\" heads, which carried neutral expressions, the main characters could be fitted with \"smiling\" and \"frowning\" heads.<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/><ref name=\"ArcherHearn94\">Archer and Hearn, p.&nbsp;94.</ref> The wigs of female puppets were made of human hair; for male puppets, [[mohair]] was used as it was softer and easier to style.<ref name=\"ArcherHearn93\"/>\n\n===Design and effects===\nThe ''Stingray'' submarine was designed by [[Reg Hill]] and built by [[Feltham]]-based company Mastermodels.<ref name=\"ArcherHearn89\"/><ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re101\"/> The Marineville model, which was created in-house, was made of wood and cardboard augmented with pieces of model kits purchased from a toy shop.<ref name=\"ArcherHearn93\">Archer and Hearn, p.&nbsp;93.</ref> It was lowered and raised by [[hydraulics]].<ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re101\"/> Most of the series' [[special effects]] shots were filmed on [[high-speed camera]]s with the footage slowed down in [[post-production]] to convey greater weight and scale.<ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re101\">La Rivi\u00e8re, p.&nbsp;101.</ref>\n\nAnderson had originally envisaged filming the underwater sequences inside a water tank,<ref name=\"O'Brien80\"/> but the cost of the specialist cameras and equipment required would have made this impractical.<ref name=\"Peel23\">Peel, p.&nbsp;23.</ref> The sequences were instead filmed by shooting a model ocean floor (mounted against a [[Cyclorama (theater)|cyclorama]])<ref name=\"ArcherHearn91\"/> through a thin [[aquarium]] and \"flying\" the puppets and scale models across the set on wires from an overhead gantry.<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/> A similar technique had been used on ''Supercar''.<ref>La Rivi\u00e8re, p.&nbsp;99.</ref> Several aquaria were used; constructed by a company that supplied fish tanks for [[London Zoo]], they were re-built with thicker glass after one of them burst due to the water pressure.<ref name=\"ArcherHearn92\">Archer and Hearn, p.&nbsp;92.</ref> Wires were painted over to make them non-reflective,<ref name=\"ArcherHearn92\"/> while [[vegetable dye]] was added to the aquaria to give the water a murky look.<ref>Sellers, p.&nbsp;91.</ref> Fans were used to simulate currents passing over characters' hair and clothing.<ref name=\"ArcherHearn93\"/>\n\nThe illusion of scenes being set underwater was enhanced by populating the aquaria with [[tropical fish]] of various sizes to create [[forced perspective]].<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/><ref name=\"Rogers83\">Rogers et al., p.&nbsp;83.</ref> [[Fish food]] was dropped at various points around the aquaria to keep the animals in shot.<ref name=\"ArcherHearn92\"/> A disc with portions cut out was placed in front of a lamp and rotated to simulate light being [[refracted]] through the ocean surface, while the water in the aquaria was disturbed to create \"ripple\" effects.<ref name=\"ArcherHearn91\"/> For the climax of the ''Stingray'' launch sequence, which sees the submarine shooting out of an underwater tunnel, part of the set was painted onto the aquarium to conceal the [[air line]] that produced the accompanying bubbles.<ref name=\"ArcherHearn92\"/><ref name=\"Meddings33\">Meddings, p.&nbsp;33.</ref> The move away from black and white sometimes caused problems as build-ups of algae in the aquaria caused the water to change colour.<ref name=\"Meddings33\"/>\n\nFor ocean surface shots, one of the problems facing the effects crew was the need to maintain a sense of realism with the scale models while working on water, which cannot be miniaturised.<ref name=\"Holliss\"/><ref name=\"Peel23\"/> Surface shots in ''Supercar'' and ''Fireball XL5'' had been filmed in a single outdoor water tank, but for ''Stingray'' a number of tanks were built inside the studio.<ref name=\"Meddings32\">Meddings, p.&nbsp;32.</ref> Lighting effects proved insufficient to make the water look blue, so it was instead dyed to give it a realistic colour.<ref name=\"Meddings34\">Meddings, p.&nbsp;34.</ref><ref>La Rivi\u00e8re, p.&nbsp;100.</ref> Various powders were added to create foam and [[whitewater]] effects for storm scenes and undersea explosions.<ref>Meddings, p.&nbsp;35.</ref> Models were controlled using wires, poles and underwater tracks and rigs.<ref name=\"Meddings32\"/><ref name=\"Meddings34\"/>\n\nEach tank incorporated a [[weir]] system whereby the back wall, and sometimes other walls, were built lower than the rest and the tank was purposely overfilled to create waterfalls.<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/><ref name=\"Hearn38\">Hearn, p.&nbsp;38.</ref> With the camera mounted at water level and facing the back of the tank, this produced an artificial horizon.<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/> To sustain the effect, the overflowing water was collected in troughs and pumped back into the tank.<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/><ref name=\"Rogers84\">Rogers et al., p.&nbsp;84.</ref> To conserve studio space, some scenes were filmed in a wedge-shaped tank built to match the camera's [[field of view]].<ref>Rogers et al., pp.&nbsp;84\u201385.</ref> One of the effects shots in the opening titles \u2013 a complex manoeuvre in which ''Stingray'' and a pursuing Mechanical Fish leap out of, and then plunge back into, the sea \u2013 was filmed in a single take.<ref name=\"ArcherHearn92\"/>\n\nShots of aircraft in flight were filmed using a technique known as the \"rolling sky\", whereby the scale model remained stationary and an illusion of movement was created by running a painted-sky canvas background in a continuous loop around two electrically-driven rollers. This system, devised by effects director [[Derek Meddings]], made aerial shots easier to film as it required very little studio space.<ref>Meddings, pp.&nbsp;36\u201337.</ref>\n\n===Opening and closing titles===\nThe [[title sequence]] consists of a series of action shots featuring undersea explosions, Marineville going to red alert and ''Stingray'' being launched to do battle with a Mechanical Fish. This is accompanied by dramatic narration from the character of Commander Shore, who warns the audience to \"Stand by for action!\" before declaring that \"Anything can happen in the next half-hour!\" In the first 26 episodes, the title sequence opens in black and white before switching to colour; for the final 13 episodes, the first few seconds were replaced with all-colour footage.<ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re103\">La Rivi\u00e8re, p.&nbsp;103.</ref>\n\nJim Sangster and Paul Condon, authors of ''Collins Telly Guide'', praise this introduction, writing that \"Of all the programmes we've looked at for this book, there is none with a title sequence as thrilling as ''Stingray''.\"<ref name=\"SangsterCondon\">{{Cite book|title=Collins Telly Guide|last1=Sangster|first1=Jim|last2=Condon|first2=Paul|year=2005|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|location=London, UK|isbn=978-0-00-719099-7|page=722}}</ref> Anthony Clark of the [[British Film Institute]] calls the sequence \"a mini-adventure in itself ... Children's TV had never before been this exciting.\"<ref name=\"Clark\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/440096/|title=''Stingray'' (1964\u201365)|last1=Clark|first1=Anthony|work=[[Screenonline]]|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|location=London, UK|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317232857/http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/440096/|archive-date=17 March 2018|url-status=live|access-date=23 February 2019}}</ref> According to [[John Peel (writer)|John Peel]], the ''Stingray'' title sequence contrasts greatly with those of ''Supercar'' and ''Fireball XL5'', which he describes as \"straight narrative openings\".<ref name=\"Peel241\">Peel, p.&nbsp;241.</ref> Peel also argues that ''Stingray'' has influenced the \"rapid cutting, pounding rhythms and extreme stylising\" of later TV title sequences.<ref name=\"Peel241\"/>\n\nThe series' [[closing titles]] focus on the [[love triangle]] between Troy, Marina and Atlanta. They feature Troy singing \"Aqua Marina\" \u2013 a song about his romantic feelings for Marina, performed by [[Gary Miller (singer)|Gary Miller]] with [[soprano]] backing vocals \u2013 while Atlanta gazes wistfully at his photograph.<ref name=\"ArcherHearn98\">Archer and Hearn, p.&nbsp;98.</ref>\n\n==Broadcast==\nIn the UK, ''Stingray'' was first broadcast on 4 October 1964 in the [[ITV Anglia|Anglia]], [[ITV Border|Border]], [[Grampian Television|Grampian]], [[Associated Television|London]] and [[Southern Television|Southern]] regions.<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/><ref name=\"ArcherHearn100\"/> It premiered in the [[ITV Channel Television|Channel]], [[Associated Television|Midlands]] and [[Westward Television|Westward]] regions on 6 October, [[Scottish Television|Scottish]] on 8 November,<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=GGgVawPscysC&dat=19641107&printsec=frontpage&hl=en] The Glasgow Herald - 7 November 1964, Page 14],</ref> and on [[Granada Television]] on 30 December.<ref name=\"Bentley2008,79\"/> Having debuted in black and white, it was broadcast in colour for the first time in December 1969.<ref name=\"ArcherHearn91\"/> The series received little publicity but replicated the success of earlier Supermarionation productions.<ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re102\"/> It was repeated on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] in 1981<ref>Bentley 2017, p.&nbsp;188.</ref> and on [[BBC2]] in the early 1990s.<ref>Archer and Hearn, p.&nbsp;260.</ref><ref>Bentley 2017, p.&nbsp;194.</ref>\n\nIn the US, the series was first broadcast in 1965.<ref>Lewis and Stempel, p.&nbsp;174.</ref> Premiering in colour, it was [[Broadcast syndication|syndicated]] across more than 100 markets with total sales exceeding \u00a33&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"ArcherHearn91\"/><ref>Rogers et al., p.&nbsp;94.</ref><ref>Bentley 2001, p.&nbsp;12.</ref> It aired on the [[Sci-Fi Channel]] in 1994.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Exploring ''Space: 1999'': An Episode Guide and Complete History of the Mid-1970s Science Fiction Television Series|last1=Muir|first1=John Kenneth|author1-link=John Kenneth Muir|year=2015|origyear=1997|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|location=Jefferson, North Carolina|isbn=978-0-786455-27-0|page=5}}</ref>\n\n==Tie-ins==\n''Stingray'' was featured in the Supermarionation [[tie-in]] comic ''[[TV Century 21]]'' from its first issue, published by [[Century 21 Merchandising|AP Films (Merchandising)]] in January 1965.<ref name=\"LaRivi\u00e8re102\"/><ref name=\"Holliss\"/> The 1960s also saw the publication of two original novels by [[Armada Books]]: ''Stingray'' and ''Stingray and the Monster'', written by John William Jennison under the pseudonym \"John Theydon\".<ref>Bentley 2001, p.&nbsp;108.</ref>\n\n===Audio episodes===\nTo supplement the TV episodes, in 1965 AP Films (Merchandising) released three \"audio adventures\" as [[7-inch]] vinyl [[EP record]]s (marketed as \"mini-albums\").<ref>Bentley 2008, p.&nbsp;367.</ref> These [[audio play]]s, each approximately 21 minutes long and featuring the voice cast from the TV series, are included as special features on the UK ''Stingray'' DVD [[box set]].\n\n{{Episode table\n|title=\n|titleR=<ref name=\"Bentley2008,354-355\">Bentley 2008, pp.&nbsp;354\u2013355.</ref>\n|aux1=\n|aux1T=Code\n|aux1R=<ref name=\"Bentley2008,354-355\"/>\n|writer=\n|writerR=<ref name=\"Bentley2008,354-355\"/>\n|aux2=\n|aux2T=Produced by\n|aux2R=<ref name=\"Bentley2008,354-355\"/>\n|episodes=\n\n{{Episode list\n|Title=Into Action With Troy Tempest\n|Aux1=MA 101\n|WrittenBy=[[Alan Fennell]]\n|Aux2=[[Desmond Saunders]]\n|ShortSummary=While investigating the disappearance of a submarine, the crew of ''Stingray'' find themselves trapped in a subterranean sea that later becomes a desert. ''This audio episode combines the plots of the TV episodes \"Stingray\", \"Deep Heat\" and \"Subterranean Sea\".''<ref>Bentley 2008, p.&nbsp;354.</ref>\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|Title=A Trip to Marineville\n|Aux1=MA 102\n|WrittenBy=Alan Fennell\n|Aux2=Desmond Saunders\n|ShortSummary=Troy gives a young boy a tour of Marineville.\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|Title=Marina Speaks\n|Aux1=MA 104\n|WrittenBy=[[Sylvia Anderson|Sylvia]] and [[Gerry Anderson]]\n|Aux2=Desmond Saunders\n|ShortSummary=Atlanta discovers a letter written by Marina which explains how her people came to be mute.<ref group=\"Note\" name=\"Marina\"/>\n}}\n}}\n\n==Reception==\nWriting in 2006, [[Robert Sellers]] described ''Stingray'' as the \"first truly classic Anderson show\", whose special effects \"have stood the test of time remarkably well.\"<ref>Sellers, p.&nbsp;92.</ref> Daniel O'Brien, author of ''SF:UK: How British Science Fiction Changed the World'', considers it to be \"perhaps the archetypal Gerry Anderson series\".<ref name=\"O'Brien81\">O'Brien, p.&nbsp;81.</ref> Andrew Blair of the website [[Den of Geek]] describes ''Stingray'' as \"the lesser of the Holy Triumvirate of Supermarionation (''[[Thunderbirds (TV series)|Thunderbirds]]'', it, and ''[[Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|Captain Scarlet]]''). It's shorter than the former, and lighter than the latter, giving it a comparatively breezy feel ... ''Stingray'' is inherently a matinee adventure, an inspiring rush of mild peril and jaunty escapades.\"<ref name=\"Blair\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/tv/stingray/24198/celebrating-stingray|title=Celebrating ''Stingray''|last1=Blair|first1=Andrew|date=23 January 2013|work=[[Den of Geek]]|publisher=Dennis Publishing|location=London, UK|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127211531/http://www.denofgeek.com/tv/stingray/24198/celebrating-stingray|archive-date=27 November 2017|url-status=live|access-date=23 February 2019}}</ref> Ranking the Anderson productions, Morgan Jeffery of [[Digital Spy]] places ''Stingray'' fourth, calling it \"a kids' adventure serial of the highest order\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/feature/g25197/gerry-anderson-series-ranked-ufo-stingray-supercar-secret-service/?slide=14|title=Ranking all of Gerry Anderson's Classic TV shows, from ''Thunderbirds'' to ''Captain Scarlet''|last1=Jeffery|first1=Morgan|date=14 April 2018|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst UK]]|location=London, UK|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603213806/http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/feature/g25197/gerry-anderson-series-ranked-ufo-stingray-supercar-secret-service/?slide=14 |archive-date=3 June 2018|url-status=live|access-date=23 February 2019}}</ref> Peel, despite praising ''Stingray'', believes that ''[[Fireball XL5]]'' and ''Thunderbirds'' had more appeal.<ref name=\"Peel1986\">{{Cite book|title=The Gerry Anderson's ''Stingray'' Files|last1=Peel|first1=John|author1-link=John Peel (writer)|year=1986|publisher=Psi Fi Movie Press|location=Los Angeles, California|page=11}}</ref>\n\nComparing ''Stingray'' to APF's earlier work, media historian Marcus Hearn writes that the series essentially \"[transfers] the format of ''Fireball XL5'' to an underwater setting.\"<ref name=\"Hearn38\"/> [[Kim Newman]] describes it as a \"patrol show\" similar to ''Supercar'' and ''Fireball XL5''.<ref name=\"Newman\">{{Cite magazine |magazine=[[Video Watchdog]] |publisher=[[Tim Lucas|Lucas, Tim]] and Lucas, Donna |location=Cincinnati, Ohio |title=DVDs: Imports: ''Thunderbirds'' \u2013 The Complete Series and ''Stingray'' \u2013 The Complete Series |oclc=646838004 |issn=1070-9991 |date=March 2002 |issue=81 |pages=68\u201372 |last=Newman|first=Kim |author1-link=Kim Newman}}</ref> Peel suggests that the setting was influenced by a 1960s vogue for undersea exploration inspired by the work of adventurers such as [[Jacques Cousteau]] and [[Thor Heyerdahl]].<ref name=\"Peel1986\"/> Clark notes that ''Stingray'', like ''Fireball XL5'', uses \"some very simple elements \u2013 a four-square hero, a fantastic craft which lends its name to the show and a mix of fast-paced action and innocent humour.\"<ref name=\"Clark\"/> Commenting on the storytelling, Paul Mavis of the website [[DVD Talk]] writes that the series employs a \"'heroes and villains' dynamic, hung on a well-worn melodramatic comic book framework (and gussied-up with sci-fi, [[Bondian]] trappings)\".<ref name=\"Mavis\"/> Blair describes the [[love triangle]] between Atlanta, Troy and Marina as an \"unusual development\" for a children's series,<ref name=\"Blair\"/> while Peel argues that ''Stingray'' saw the peak of the \"[[tongue-in-cheek]] humour\" favoured by Gerry Anderson.<ref name=\"Peel240\"/>\n\nMike Fillis of ''[[TV Zone]]'' magazine regards ''Stingray'' as less \"ambitious\" than ''Thunderbirds'' but compares its \"self-awareness\" and \"looseness\" favourably to the \"po-faced rigidity\" of ''Captain Scarlet''. He also praises the series' \"well-drawn\" characters and describes its water-based special effects as \"surprisingly elegant\".<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=Reviews: Merchandise: ''Stingray''|journal=TV Zone|last1=Fillis|first1=Mike|issue=138|date=May 2001|publication-date=April 2001|publisher=Visual Imagination|location=London, UK|issn=0957-3844|oclc=226121852|page=82}}</ref> [[Paul Cornell]], [[Martin Day]] and [[Keith Topping]], authors of ''The Guinness Book of Classic British TV'', regard the effects as more \"realistic\" than those of earlier Anderson series. They also argue that while many episodes were \"predictable and corny\", the series had a \"knowingness and a love of character that made the whole thing charming.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Cornell|first1=Paul|last2=Day|first2=Martin|last3=Topping|first3=Keith|author1-link=Paul Cornell|author2-link=Martin Day|author3-link=Keith Topping|title=The Guinness Book of Classic British TV|editor1-last=Marshall|editor1-first=Anne|year=1996|origyear=1993|edition=2nd|publisher=[[Guinness Publishing]]|location=London, UK|isbn=978-0-85112-628-9|page=330}}</ref>\n\nSome criticism has been directed at the puppetry and effects. Mavis suggests that the series' use of aquaria makes the underwater scenes look \"a tad creaky\" but believes that they compare well to contemporary feature film effects.<ref name=\"Mavis\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/67380/stingray-the-complete-series-50th-anniversary-edition/|title=''Stingray: The Complete Series'' \u2013 50th Anniversary Edition|last1=Mavis|first1=Paul|date=13 January 2015|work=[[DVD Talk]]|publisher=[[Internet Brands]]|location=El Segundo, California|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911135340/https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/67380/stingray-the-complete-series-50th-anniversary-edition/|archive-date=11 September 2017|url-status=live|access-date=23 February 2019}}</ref> [[Glenn Erickson]] comments that as in other Supermarionation series, the puppets' lack of mobility makes their scenes \"rather static\". He also notes that due to this limitation, movement is often kept off-screen: \"Almost every capture by Aquaphibians ellipses difficult-to-film interaction, skipping straight to static talking scenes instead.\"<ref name=\"Erickson\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/5364/stingray-the-complete-series/|title=''Stingray: The Complete Series''|last1=Erickson|first1=Glenn|author1-link=Glenn Erickson|date=10 January 2003|work=DVD Talk|publisher=Internet Brands|location=El Segundo, California|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010010537/https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/5364/stingray-the-complete-series/|archive-date=10 October 2017|url-status=live|access-date=23 February 2019}}</ref> However, Mavis and Erickson both comment positively on the series overall. For Mavis, ''Stingray'' is \"generally delightful, sometimes weird\" and boasts \"almost big-screen-worthy direction and editing\".<ref name=\"Mavis\"/> Erickson argues that the episodes not featuring Titan provide \"welcome detours from the central aggression theme\", and sums up ''Stingray'' as a \"silly but captivating kiddie show\".<ref name=\"Erickson\"/>\n\nFor Jon E. Lewis and Penny Stempel, authors of ''Cult TV: The Essential Critical Guide'', the series featured \"plenty of kiddie-time exciting narrative action, while the more sophisticated could enjoy its proclivity to spoof virtually everything which passed its periscope.\"<ref>Lewis and Stempel, p.&nbsp;175.</ref> Sangster and Condon argue that while ''Stingray'' was primarily a children's series, it was also the first Anderson production with adult appeal. Comparing ''Stingray'' to ''Thunderbirds'', they describe the former's episodes as \"mercifully shorter, leading to tighter plotting and an engaging simplicity\".<ref name=\"SangsterCondon\"/> Newman considers ''Stingray'' to be \"livelier\" than ''Thunderbirds'' due to the romantic tension between the main characters and for \"playing up to the childish streak of its hero\". However, he also expresses surprise at the number of fantasy and [[Dream sequence|dream episodes]] and suggests that ''Stingray'', like its successor, conveys \"square, almost 1950s\" attitudes towards race through its regular depictions of \"silver- and green-skinned evil undersea races, not to mention the odd caricatured Arab baddie\".<ref name=\"Newman\"/>\n\nPraise has been directed at the music. Erickson describes it as \"corny retro\" and appropriate to the series' tone,<ref name=\"Erickson\"/> while Clark calls it the \"best underwater adventure music ever written\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sci-fi-online.com/00_revs/r2009/music/09-05-07_stingray.html|title=''Stingray: Original Television Soundtrack''|last1=Clark|first1=Anthony|work=sci-fi-online.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027043633/http://www.sci-fi-online.com/00_revs/r2009/music/09-05-07_stingray.html|archive-date=27 October 2014|url-status=live|access-date=23 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nMedia historian [[Nicholas J. Cull]] comments that through its depiction of the World Aquanaut Security Patrol (WASP), ''Stingray'' is one of several Gerry Anderson series to \"assume the development of [[world government]] and world security institutions\" and \"reflect the 1960s vogue for stories set in secret organisations with extravagant acronyms.\" He compares the premise of the series to the [[Cold War]], noting the conflict between WASP and the undersea races and the latter's use of spies to infiltrate human society. Cull names \"Marineville Traitor\", which focuses on a hunt for an \"enemy within\", as one episode with an \"especially strong Cold War flavour\". He also notes that while Anderson's productions often depict [[nuclear technology]] as a hazard, ''Stingray'' also portrays it in a positive light: the ''Stingray'' submarine itself, for example, is nuclear-powered.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Cull | first1 = Nicholas J. | author1-link = Nicholas J. Cull | date=August 2006 | title = Was Captain Black Really Red? The TV Science Fiction of Gerry Anderson in its Cold War Context | journal = Media History | volume = 12 | issue = 2 | publisher = [[Routledge]] | issn = 1368-8804 | oclc = 364457089 | doi = 10.1080/13688800600808005 | pages = 193\u2013207}}</ref>\n\nSarah Kurchak of [[The A.V. Club]] argues that Titan and the Aquaphibians represent a \"more classically Cold War-style villainous [[Other (philosophy)|Other]]\" compared to villains of earlier Supermarionation series. She adds that in ''Stingray'', \"the battle lines between land and sea are clearly defined, the enemy is always watching, and the target of their aggression is always close to home.\" Kurchak also suggests that through his \"multiple nightmares\" about threats to Marineville, the character of Troy Tempest serves to embody Cold War anxieties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tv.avclub.com/puppet-state-the-growing-cold-war-anxiety-of-gerry-and-1798246195|title=Puppet State: The Growing Cold War Anxiety of Gerry Anderson's Supermarionation Shows|last1=Kurchak|first1=Sarah|date=1 April 2016|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|location=Chicago, Illinois|access-date=29 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180114211952/https://tv.avclub.com/puppet-state-the-growing-cold-war-anxiety-of-gerry-and-1798246195|archive-date=14 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> O'Brien writes that ''Stingray'' contains \"more than a touch of the Cold War ethos\", arguing that Titan \"could have easily belonged to an underwater branch of the [[Soviet Bloc]].\"<ref name=\"O'Brien81\"/>\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn the film ''[[Aquaman (2018 film)|Aquaman]]'' (2018), ''Stingray'' is briefly seen playing on character Tom Curry's television set; the scene was included by director [[James Wan]] at the behest of fellow director [[Edgar Wright]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/how-james-wan-honored-an-aquaman-easter-egg-request-from-edgar-wright|title=How James Wan Honored an ''Aquaman'' Easter Egg Request from Edgar Wright|last1=Weiss|first1=Josh|work=[[Syfy|syfy.com]]|publisher=[[NBCUniversal Media]]|location=New York City, New York|date=26 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181226221254/https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/how-james-wan-honored-an-aquaman-easter-egg-request-from-edgar-wright|archive-date=26 December 2018|url-status=live|access-date=27 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Works cited===\n* {{Cite book | last1 = Archer | first1 = Simon | author1-link = Simon Archer (author) | last2 = Hearn | first2 = Marcus | title = What Made ''Thunderbirds'' Go! The Authorised Biography of Gerry Anderson | year = 2002 | publisher = [[BBC Books]] | location = London, UK | isbn = 978-0-563-53481-5}}\n** Originally published as: {{Cite book|last1=Archer|first1=Simon|last2=Nicholls|first2=Stan|author2-link=Stan Nicholls|title=Gerry Anderson: The Authorised Biography|year=1996|publisher=[[Legend Books]]|location=London, UK|isbn=978-0-09-922442-6}}\n* {{Cite book | last1 = Bentley | first1 = Chris | editor1-last = Hearn | editor1-first = Marcus | title = Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons: The Vault | year = 2017 | publisher = Signum Books | location = Cambridge, UK | isbn=978-0-995519-12-1}}\n* {{Cite book | last1 = Bentley | first1 = Chris | title = The Complete Book of Captain Scarlet | year = 2001 | publisher = [[Carlton Books]] | location = London, UK | isbn = 978-1-84222-405-2}}\n* {{Cite book | last1 = Bentley | first1 = Chris | title = The Complete Gerry Anderson: The Authorised Episode Guide | publisher = Reynolds & Hearn | location = London, UK | edition = 4th | year = 2008 | origyear = 2001 | isbn = 978-1-905287-74-1}}\n* {{Cite book | last1 = Fryer | first1 = Ian | title=The Worlds of Gerry and Sylvia Anderson: The Story Behind International Rescue | year = 2016 | publisher = Fonthill Media | isbn = 978-1-78155-504-0}}\n* {{Cite book | title = Thunderbirds: The Vault | last1 = Hearn | first1 = Marcus | year = 2015 | publisher = [[Virgin Books]] | location = London, UK | isbn = 978-0-753-55635-1}}\n* {{Cite book | last1 = La Rivi\u00e8re | first1 = Stephen | title = Filmed in Supermarionation: A History of the Future | year = 2009 | publisher = [[Hermes Press]] 