{"title_page": "Maricopa, Arizona", "text_new": "{{about|the city in Arizona|the county|Maricopa County, Arizona|the city in California|Maricopa, California}}\n{{short description|City in Arizona, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = \n| official_name                   = Maricopa\n| settlement_type                 = [[City]]\n| image_skyline                   = Maricopa_Arizona.jpg\n| imagesize                       = \n| image_caption                   = Residential developments dominate the landscape of Maricopa\n| image_map                       = Pinal County Arizona Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Maricopa Highlighted 0444410.svg\n| mapsize                         = 250px\n| map_caption                     = Location of Maricopa in Pinal County, Arizona\n| image_map1                      = \n| mapsize1                        = \n| map_caption1                    = \n| pushpin_map                     = USA\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in the United States\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|33|3|24|N|112|2|48|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = [[United States]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of counties in Arizona|County]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Arizona]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Pinal County, Arizona|Pinal]]\n| established_title               = \n| established_date                = \n| established_title2              = Incorporated\n| established_date2               = 2003\n| government_type                 = \n| leader_title                    = [[Mayor]]\n| leader_name                     = Christian Price\n| leader_title1                   = [[Vice Mayor]]\n| leader_name1                    = Henry Wade\n| unit_pref                       = Imperial\n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_04.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jul 1, 2019}}</ref>\n| area_magnitude                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = 111.10\n| area_total_sq_mi                = 42.90\n| area_land_km2                   = 110.85\n| area_land_sq_mi                 = 42.80\n| area_water_km2                  = 0.26\n| area_water_sq_mi                = 0.10\n| elevation_m                     = 358\n| elevation_ft                    = 1190\n| population_total                = 43482\n| population_as_of                = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web |title=Us Census Bureau Quick Facts |url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/maricopacityarizona,US/PST045218 |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=May 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| population_density_km2          = 451.29\n| population_density_sq_mi        = 1168.84\n| population_est                  = 50024\n| pop_est_as_of                   = 2018\n| pop_est_footnotes               = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n| postal_code_type                = [[ZIP code]]\n| postal_code                     = 85138, 85139\n| area_code                       = [[Area code 520|520]]\n| website                         = http://www.maricopa-az.gov/web/\n| leader_title2                   = [[City Council]]\n| leader_name2                    = Marvin Brown, Julia Gusse, Vincent Manfredi, Nancy Smith, Rich Vitiello\n| leader_title3                   = [[City Manager]]\n| leader_name3                    = Rick Horst\n| leader_title4                   = [[City Clerk]]\n| leader_name4                    = Vanessa Bueras\n| timezone                        = [[Mountain Standard Time Zone|MST]] (no [[Daylight savings time|DST]])\n| utc_offset                      = -7\n| timezone_DST                    = \n| utc_offset_DST                  = \n| blank_name                      = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info                      = 04-44410\n| blank1_name                     = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n| blank1_info                     = {{GNIS 4|7694}}  \n| footnote                        = \n}}\n\n'''Maricopa''' is a city in the [[Gila River Valley]] in [[Arizona]]. With an estimated 50,024 residents as of 2018,<ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web |title=Us Census Bureau Quick Facts |url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/maricopacityarizona,US/PST045218 |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=May 24, 2019}}</ref> Maricopa is the second most populous incorporated city in [[Pinal County, Arizona|Pinal County]] and eighteenth most populous in Arizona.<ref name=\"USCensusQuickFacts\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/maricopacityarizona,US/PST045218|title=Population Estimates July 1, 2018|accessdate=January 6, 2019}}</ref> Maricopa forms part of the [[Phoenix metropolitan area]].\n\n==History==\nMaricopa has had three locations over the years: [[Maricopa Wells, Arizona|Maricopa Wells]], '''Maricopaville''' and '''Maricopa Junction;''' the latter gradually became known as Maricopa. It started as an oasis around a series of watering holes eight miles north of present-day Maricopa, and about a mile west of Pima Butte. European-American traders and travelers called it Maricopa Wells. Several of Arizona\u2019s rivers, the Gila, Santa Cruz, Vekol and Santa Rosa provided this oasis in the desert with an ample supply of water during this period of time.\n\nDuring the late 1800s, Maricopa Wells was one of the most important relay stations along the [[San Antonio-San Diego Mail Line]] and the later more famous [[Butterfield Overland Mail in New Mexico Territory#3rd Division|Butterfield Overland Mail]] Route.  Although little remains of this once bustling community, it played an important part in the progress and development of the Southwest. It was one of the best-known spots in Arizona during this period of time because it had a reliable source of water, and offered an abundant supply of food. The peaceful Pima and Maricopa farmers who lived and farmed nearby sold supplies to travelers and migrants.\n\nThe most prosperous period of time for Maricopa Wells was in the 1870s. During this time the trading center at the Wells provided water and food for not only the east-west travelers, but those who traveled to the north to Phoenix. Fairly good roads had been built by James A. Moore, the proprietor at Maricopa Wells, to all points north, and the Wells was a constant hubbub of activity.\n\nMaricopaville developed south and west of the Wells, following construction of a railroad line from this terminus to Phoenix. In 1879, the Southern Pacific Railroad was in the process of building a railroad line from Yuma to Tucson, and a second railroad line was to be built from Maricopaville, wrapping around the western edge of South Mountain into [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]. With the railroad, Maricopaville took on the appearance of a gold rush California boom town, as men worked day and night building hotels, saloons, warehouses, restaurants, theaters, etc.  One newspaper of the time reckoned that with its thousands of people and good location, Maricopaville would be an ideal choice for the location of the state capital.\n\nBut the railroad never built the anticipated line from Maricopaville into Phoenix.  [[Tempe, Arizona|Tempe]] also wanted to be on the railroad line and lobbied the territorial government to gain a stop. Officials agreed. The settlement known as Maricopaville was essentially rebuilt three miles to the east (to the present location of Maricopa) in the early 1880s, in order to accommodate the Maricopa & Phoenix line, planned to go through Kyrene and Tempe to the north on the way to Phoenix. The first train departed from Maricopa for Phoenix on July 4, 1887. All east-west rail travelers had to stop at Maricopa, and those who wanted to go north had to shift to the M & P Railroad.<ref>''Reflections of a Desert Town'', Patricia Brock</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maricopachamber.org/futureresident/history.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 24, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090916061444/http://www.maricopachamber.org/futureresident/history.php |archivedate=September 16, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inmaricopa.com/COMMUNITY/History/tabid/131/Default.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 24, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100723195058/http://www.inmaricopa.com/COMMUNITY/History/tabid/131/Default.aspx |archivedate=July 23, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nMaricopa was officially incorporated as a city on October 15, 2003, becoming the 88th incorporated municipality in Arizona.  Between 2000 and 2010, the city's population grew from 1,040 residents to 43,482, an increase of 4080%.<ref name=\"2010 Census\">{{cite web|url=http://2010.census.gov/news/xls/cb11cn76_az_2010redistr.xls|title=U.S. Census Data|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|date=March 10, 2011|accessdate=March 10, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322113902/http://2010.census.gov/news/xls/cb11cn76_az_2010redistr.xls|archivedate=March 22, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2018, estimates approved by the US Census Bureau and Arizona State Demographer's Office put Maricopa's population at 51,977 pushing the city over the 50,000 mark for the first time.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.maricopa-az.gov/web/city-news-feed/3498-maricopa-s-population-reaches-over-50-000|title=Maricopa's Population Reaches Over 50,000!|last=Wolfe|first=Adam|website=City of Maricopa|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref>\n\nA part of the city is within the boundaries of the [[Ak-Chin Indian Community]]. The small, federally recognized tribe has developed [[Harrah's Ak-Chin Casino]] and related resort, a multi-entertainment cinema complex, and operates a golf course; all are open to the public and draw attendees from Maricopa as well as the greater Phoenix area. In addition the tribe operates the Ak-Chin Regional Airport and an industrial park. A 2011 study said that its casino and resort made up a large part of the economy of Pinal County, in terms of number of jobs and revenue generated.{{Citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n==Geography and climate==\nMaricopa is located at {{Coord|33|3|24|N|112|2|48|W|type:city}} (33.056702, -112.046656).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=April 23, 2011|date=February 12, 2011|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|31.9|sqmi|km2}}, all of it land.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_DP_G001&prodType=table|title=American FactFinder - Results|first=U.S. Census|last=Bureau|website=factfinder2.census.gov}}</ref>\n\nThe topography in Maricopa is flat with several mountain ranges 10 to 20 miles away.  The elevation of Maricopa is 1190 feet.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Maricopa, AZ\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F =  86\n|Feb record high F =  90\n|Mar record high F = 100\n|Apr record high F = 106\n|May record high F = 113\n|Jun record high F = 122\n|Jul record high F = 124\n|Aug record high F = 117\n|Sep record high F = 113\n|Oct record high F = 109\n|Nov record high F =  95\n|Dec record high F =  84\n|year record high F =124\n|Jan high F =  68\n|Feb high F =  73\n|Mar high F =  79\n|Apr high F =  88\n|May high F =  98\n|Jun high F = 107\n|Jul high F = 108\n|Aug high F = 106\n|Sep high F = 102\n|Oct high F =  90\n|Nov high F =  77\n|Dec high F =  67\n|year high F =\n|Jan low F = 36\n|Feb low F = 39\n|Mar low F = 44\n|Apr low F = 50\n|May low F = 59\n|Jun low F = 68\n|Jul low F = 77\n|Aug low F = 76\n|Sep low F = 68\n|Oct low F = 54\n|Nov low F = 42\n|Dec low F = 35\n|year low F =\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation inch = 0.83\n|Feb precipitation inch = 0.91\n|Mar precipitation inch = 1.00\n|Apr precipitation inch = 0.28\n|May precipitation inch = 0.17\n|Jun precipitation inch = 0.08\n|Jul precipitation inch = 0.98\n|Aug precipitation inch = 0.96\n|Sep precipitation inch = 0.72\n|Oct precipitation inch = 0.47\n|Nov precipitation inch = 0.58\n|Dec precipitation inch = 0.97\n|year precipitation inch =7.98\n|source 1 = The Weather Channel<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USAZ0131|title= Monthly Averages for Maricopa, AZ | publisher=Weather.com |year=2010 |accessdate=September 17, 2012}}</ref>\n|date=September 2012\n}}\n\n===Surrounding municipalities===\n{{Geographic location\n|Northwest = [[Goodyear, Arizona|Goodyear]]\n|North     = [[Gila River Indian Community]]\n|Northeast = Gila River Indian Community\n|West      = [[Ak-Chin Village, Arizona|Ak-Chin Village]]\n|Center    = Maricopa\n|South     = [[Stanfield, Arizona|Stanfield]]\n|Southwest = Palo Verde Mountains\n|Southeast = [[Casa Grande, Arizona|Casa Grande]]\n|East      = Gila River Indian Community\n}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|2000= 1040\n|2010= 43482\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=50024\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=<center>U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref></center>\n}}\n\nAs of the census of 2010, there were 43,482 people, 14,359 households, and 11,110 families residing in the city. The population density was 1,356.8 people per square mile (526.4/km<sup>2</sup>). There were 17,240 housing units at an average density of 540.4 per square mile (208.7/km<sup>2</sup>). The racial makeup of the city was 70.2% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 9.7% [[African American (U.S. Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 2.0% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 4.1% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.3% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 8.5% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 5.3% from two or more races. 24.4% of the population is [[Hispanics in the United States|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 14,359 households out of which 47.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 37.5% were married couples living together, 10.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 22.6% were non-families. 15.6% of all households were made up of individuals and 2.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 3.03 and the average family size was 3.38.<ref name=\"factfinder2.census\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid%3DDEC_10_DP_DPDP1%26prodType%3Dtable |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 23, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305164937/http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_DP_DPDP1&prodType=table |archivedate=March 5, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 32.5% under the age of 18, 6.2% from 18 to 24, 35% from 25 to 44, 19.8% from 45 to 64, and 6.5% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 31.2 years. For every 100 females, there were 98.5 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.8 males.\n\nAccording to 2009 Census Bureau estimates, the median income for a household in the city was $67,692, and the median income for a family was $69,818.  The per capita income for the city was $27,618. About 3.7% of families and 5.2% of the population were below the poverty line.\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n=== Roads ===\nMaricopa is primarily served by [[Arizona State Route 347]], a north-south highway that connects to [[Interstate 10 in Arizona|Interstate 10]], approximately 14 miles north of Maricopa, as well as [[Arizona State Route 84]] 11 miles south of Maricopa. State Route 84 then ends at [[Interstate 8]] approximately 6 miles west of State Route 347. Within Maricopa, State Route 347 is John Wayne Parkway. As it leaves the city for the [[Gila River Indian Community]] to the north or the [[Ak-Chin Indian Community]] to the south, the road changes names to Maricopa Road. A portion of old State Route 347 within Maricopa also exists as Maricopa Road.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinalcentral.com/maricopa_monitor/news/addresses-for-maricopa-road-properties-to-officially-change-dec/article_069a5354-dc5b-549e-8ce7-52636a887fe4.html|title=Addresses for Maricopa Road properties to officially change Dec. 1|last=|first=|date=|website=PinalCentral|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMaricopa is also served by [[Arizona State Route 238]], which connects Maricopa to the town of [[Mobile, Arizona|Mobile]], which is incorporated into the city of [[Goodyear, Arizona|Goodyear]]. Past Mobile, State Route 238 becomes a county route that connects to [[Arizona State Route 85]] in [[Gila Bend, Arizona|Gila Bend]]. State Route 238 and Mobile Road designations are used interchangeably. State Route 238 ends at State Route 347, and continues east as Smith-Enke Road, a major east-west corridor for the city of Maricopa. Maricopa-Casa Grande Highway also makes up a major corridor for the city, connecting it to the city of [[Casa Grande, Arizona|Casa Grande]]. This road parallels the Union Pacific Railroad at a diagonal, ultimately becoming Plainview Street within Maricopa and Cottonwood Lane in Casa Grande.\n\n=== Rail ===\n[[File:California-Zephyr-MaricopaAZ.JPG|thumb|California Zephyr railcar at the Maricopa, AZ [[Amtrak]] station]]Maricopa is located on a Union Pacific Railroad line. The city is currently the closest stop to [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] on [[Amtrak]]'s ''[[Sunset Limited]]'' and ''[[Texas Eagle]]'' trains. The [[Maricopa (Amtrak station)|Maricopa depot]] opened in 2001, originally in a converted passenger rail car but now in a metal building.\n\n=== Utilities ===\nMaricopa is served by the following utilities:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maricopa-az.gov/our-city/residents/utilities-services-in-maricopa|title=Utilities & Services in Maricopa|last=|first=|date=|website=City of Maricopa, AZ|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n* Cable: Orbitel Communications\n* Electricity: Electrical District #3\n* Natural Gas: [[Southwest Gas]]\n* Telephone/DSL: [[CenturyLink]]\n* Water: Global Water (Santa Cruz Water Company, Palo Verde Utilities), Maricopa Domestic Water Improvement District\n\n=== Bus ===\nThe City of Maricopa operates the City Of Maricopa Express Transit (COMET), which provides local bus service.<ref>{{Cite web| title = COMET Transit System {{!}} Maricopa, AZ| accessdate = 2020-02-03| url = https://www.maricopa-az.gov/departments/development-services/transportation/comet-transit-system}}</ref>\n\n==Municipal organization==\nMaricopa is governed by a Council-Manager form of government. This type of government structure combines the political leadership of elected officials with the managerial experience of an appointed professional manager. The City Council and City Manager work as partners to direct and guide local government.\n\nThe Maricopa City Council consists of the Mayor and six City Council members. The Mayor is elected to serve a four-year term and the City Council members are elected to serve four-year terms on a rotating basis. City Council meetings are held on the first and third Tuesdays of the month.\n\nThere are 10 citizen advisory groups that guide the Maricopa City Council on a myriad of activity. They are the Board of Adjustment, Heritage District Advisory Committee, Industrial Development Authority Board, Merit Board, Parks, Recreation and Library Advisory Committee, Planning and Zoning Commission, Public Safety Personnel Retirement System Board, Transportation Advisory Committee and the Youth Council. Selection to these groups is by City Council action.\n\nThe City is organized into nine departments: the City Manager's Office, the City Clerk's Office, Community Services, Development Services, Economic Development, Finance, Fire, Human Services and the Police Department. More than 250 individuals work for the municipality.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Civic and nonprofit organizations==\n*F.O.R. Maricopa - local [[food bank]]\n*Maricopa Gun Club- local gun club\n*Maricopa Historical Society - area historical organization\n*Maricopa Motorcycle Riders  - local group of riders; all bikes allowed\n*Maricopa Seniors  - area senior citizen group\n* [http://www.momdoccharities.org/ MomDoc Charities]\n*[[Pet Social Worker / Tails of Hope Rescue]] - local animal [[rescue group]]\n*Recycling Association of Maricopa (R.A.M.) - community drop-off recycling\n*Thunderbird Arena Community Council (TACC) - area organization supporting the renovation of the Thunderbird Farms Arena\n\n==Education facilities==\n\n=== Public school districts ===\n\n*[[Maricopa Unified School District]]\n*[[Mobile Elementary School District]]\n\n=== Public elementary schools ===\n\n* Butterfield Elementary School\n* Mobile Elementary School\n* Maricopa Elementary School\n* Pima Butte Elementary School\n* Saddleback Elementary School\n* Santa Cruz Elementary School\n* Santa Rosa Elementary School\n\n=== Public middle schools ===\n\n* Desert Wind Middle School\n* Maricopa Wells Middle School\n\n=== Public high school ===\n\n*[[Maricopa High School]]\n\n=== Charter schools ===\n\n* Graysmark Academy\n* Holsteiner Agricultural School\n* Leading Edge Academy\n* [https://maricopa.legacytraditional.org/ Legacy Traditional School-Maricopa Campus]\n* Sequoia Pathway Academy\n\n=== Community college ===\n\n* [[Central Arizona College]]\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Bristol Palin]], daughter of former Vice Presidential candidate [[Sarah Palin]], bought a house and lived in Maricopa for two years before returning to Alaska.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/40804372/ns/us_news-life/|title=New Ariz. homeowner: Bristol Palin|date=December 24, 2010|publisher=MSNBC|work=Today|accessdate=January 2, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227085708/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/40804372/ns/us_news-life|archivedate=December 27, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>[http://www.zillow.com/blog/2012-05-08/bristol-palin-no-longer-an-arizona-homeowner/ \"Bristol Palin No Longer an Arizona Homeowner\"]. ''Zillow''. May 2012.</ref>\n*Former State Senator [[Steve Smith (Arizona politician)|Steve Smith]] resides in Maricopa.\"\nTony Beets, from the show Gold Rush, Lives in Maricopa.(County land records)\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.maricopa-az.gov/ City of Maricopa]\n\n{{Pinal County, Arizona}}\n{{Phoenix Metropolitan Area}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Former census-designated places in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Cities in Pinal County, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Phoenix metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 2003]]\n[[Category:Maricopa, Arizona]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the city in Arizona|the county|Maricopa County, Arizona|the city in California|Maricopa, California}}\n{{short description|City in Arizona, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = \n| official_name                   = Maricopa\n| settlement_type                 = [[City]]\n| image_skyline                   = Maricopa_Arizona.jpg\n| imagesize                       = \n| image_caption                   = Residential developments dominate the landscape of Maricopa\n| image_map                       = File:Pinal County Arizona Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Maricopa Highlighted 0444410.svg\n| mapsize                         = 250px\n| map_caption                     = Location of Maricopa in Pinal County, Arizona\n| image_map1                      = \n| mapsize1                        = \n| map_caption1                    = \n| pushpin_map                     = USA\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in the United States\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|33|3|24|N|112|2|48|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = [[United States]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of counties in Arizona|County]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Arizona]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Pinal County, Arizona|Pinal]]\n| established_title               = \n| established_date                = \n| established_title2              = Incorporated\n| established_date2               = 2003\n| government_type                 = \n| leader_title                    = [[Mayor]]\n| leader_name                     = Christian Price\n| leader_title1                   = [[Vice Mayor]]\n| leader_name1                    = Henry Wade\n| unit_pref                       = Imperial\n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_04.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jul 1, 2019}}</ref>\n| area_magnitude                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = 111.10\n| area_total_sq_mi                = 42.90\n| area_land_km2                   = 110.85\n| area_land_sq_mi                 = 42.80\n| area_water_km2                  = 0.26\n| area_water_sq_mi                = 0.10\n| elevation_m                     = 358\n| elevation_ft                    = 1190\n| population_total                = 43482\n| population_as_of                = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web |title=Us Census Bureau Quick Facts |url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/maricopacityarizona,US/PST045218 |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=May 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| population_density_km2          = 451.29\n| population_density_sq_mi        = 1168.84\n| population_est                  = 50024\n| pop_est_as_of                   = 2018\n| pop_est_footnotes               = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n| postal_code_type                = [[ZIP code]]\n| postal_code                     = 85138, 85139\n| area_code                       = [[Area code 520|520]]\n| website                         = http://www.maricopa-az.gov/web/\n| leader_title2                   = [[City Council]]\n| leader_name2                    = Marvin Brown, Julia Gusse, Vincent Manfredi, Nancy Smith, Rich Vitiello\n| leader_title3                   = [[City Manager]]\n| leader_name3                    = Rick Horst\n| leader_title4                   = [[City Clerk]]\n| leader_name4                    = Vanessa Bueras\n| timezone                        = [[Mountain Standard Time Zone|MST]] (no [[Daylight savings time|DST]])\n| utc_offset                      = -7\n| timezone_DST                    = \n| utc_offset_DST                  = \n| GNIS_id                         = 7694\n| blank_name                      = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info                      = 04-44410\n| blank1_name                     = \n| blank1_info                     = \n| footnote                        = \n}}\n\n'''Maricopa''' is a city in the [[Gila River Valley]] in [[Arizona]]. With an estimated 50,024 residents as of 2018,<ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web |title=Us Census Bureau Quick Facts |url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/maricopacityarizona,US/PST045218 |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=May 24, 2019}}</ref> Maricopa is the second most populous incorporated city in [[Pinal County, Arizona|Pinal County]] and eighteenth most populous in Arizona.<ref name=\"USCensusQuickFacts\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/maricopacityarizona,US/PST045218|title=Population Estimates July 1, 2018|accessdate=January 6, 2019}}</ref> Maricopa forms part of the [[Phoenix metropolitan area]].\n\n==History==\nMaricopa has had three locations over the years: [[Maricopa Wells, Arizona|Maricopa Wells]], '''Maricopaville''' and '''Maricopa Junction;''' the latter gradually became known as Maricopa. It started as an oasis around a series of watering holes eight miles north of present-day Maricopa, and about a mile west of Pima Butte. European-American traders and travelers called it Maricopa Wells. Several of Arizona\u2019s rivers, the Gila, Santa Cruz, Vekol and Santa Rosa provided this oasis in the desert with an ample supply of water during this period of time.\n\nDuring the late 1800s, Maricopa Wells was one of the most important relay stations along the [[San Antonio-San Diego Mail Line]] and the later more famous [[Butterfield Overland Mail in New Mexico Territory#3rd Division|Butterfield Overland Mail]] Route.  Although little remains of this once bustling community, it played an important part in the progress and development of the Southwest. It was one of the best-known spots in Arizona during this period of time because it had a reliable source of water, and offered an abundant supply of food. The peaceful Pima and Maricopa farmers who lived and farmed nearby sold supplies to travelers and migrants.\n\nThe most prosperous period of time for Maricopa Wells was in the 1870s. During this time the trading center at the Wells provided water and food for not only the east-west travelers, but those who traveled to the north to Phoenix. Fairly good roads had been built by James A. Moore, the proprietor at Maricopa Wells, to all points north, and the Wells was a constant hubbub of activity.\n\nMaricopaville developed south and west of the Wells, following construction of a railroad line from this terminus to Phoenix. In 1879, the Southern Pacific Railroad was in the process of building a railroad line from Yuma to Tucson, and a second railroad line was to be built from Maricopaville, wrapping around the western edge of South Mountain into [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]. With the railroad, Maricopaville took on the appearance of a gold rush California boom town, as men worked day and night building hotels, saloons, warehouses, restaurants, theaters, etc.  One newspaper of the time reckoned that with its thousands of people and good location, Maricopaville would be an ideal choice for the location of the state capital.\n\nBut the railroad never built the anticipated line from Maricopaville into Phoenix.  [[Tempe, Arizona|Tempe]] also wanted to be on the railroad line and lobbied the territorial government to gain a stop. Officials agreed. The settlement known as Maricopaville was essentially rebuilt three miles to the east (to the present location of Maricopa) in the early 1880s, in order to accommodate the Maricopa & Phoenix line, planned to go through Kyrene and Tempe to the north on the way to Phoenix. The first train departed from Maricopa for Phoenix on July 4, 1887. All east-west rail travelers had to stop at Maricopa, and those who wanted to go north had to shift to the M & P Railroad.<ref>''Reflections of a Desert Town'', Patricia Brock</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maricopachamber.org/futureresident/history.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 24, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090916061444/http://www.maricopachamber.org/futureresident/history.php |archivedate=September 16, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inmaricopa.com/COMMUNITY/History/tabid/131/Default.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 24, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100723195058/http://www.inmaricopa.com/COMMUNITY/History/tabid/131/Default.aspx |archivedate=July 23, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nMaricopa was officially incorporated as a city on October 15, 2003, becoming the 88th incorporated municipality in Arizona.  Between 2000 and 2010, the city's population grew from 1,040 residents to 43,482, an increase of 4080%.<ref name=\"2010 Census\">{{cite web|url=http://2010.census.gov/news/xls/cb11cn76_az_2010redistr.xls|title=U.S. Census Data|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|date=March 10, 2011|accessdate=March 10, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322113902/http://2010.census.gov/news/xls/cb11cn76_az_2010redistr.xls|archivedate=March 22, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2018, estimates approved by the US Census Bureau and Arizona State Demographer's Office put Maricopa's population at 51,977 pushing the city over the 50,000 mark for the first time.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.maricopa-az.gov/web/city-news-feed/3498-maricopa-s-population-reaches-over-50-000|title=Maricopa's Population Reaches Over 50,000!|last=Wolfe|first=Adam|website=City of Maricopa|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref>\n\nA part of the city is within the boundaries of the [[Ak-Chin Indian Community]]. The small, federally recognized tribe has developed [[Harrah's Ak-Chin Casino]] and related resort, a multi-entertainment cinema complex, and operates a golf course; all are open to the public and draw attendees from Maricopa as well as the greater Phoenix area. In addition the tribe operates the Ak-Chin Regional Airport and an industrial park. A 2011 study said that its casino and resort made up a large part of the economy of Pinal County, in terms of number of jobs and revenue generated.{{Citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n==Geography and climate==\nMaricopa is located at {{Coord|33|3|24|N|112|2|48|W|type:city}} (33.056702, -112.046656).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=April 23, 2011|date=February 12, 2011|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|31.9|sqmi|km2}}, all of it land.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_DP_G001&prodType=table|title=American FactFinder - Results|first=U.S. Census|last=Bureau|website=factfinder2.census.gov}}</ref>\n\nThe topography in Maricopa is flat with several mountain ranges 10 to 20 miles away.  The elevation of Maricopa is 1190 feet.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Maricopa, AZ\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F =  86\n|Feb record high F =  90\n|Mar record high F = 100\n|Apr record high F = 106\n|May record high F = 113\n|Jun record high F = 122\n|Jul record high F = 124\n|Aug record high F = 117\n|Sep record high F = 113\n|Oct record high F = 109\n|Nov record high F =  95\n|Dec record high F =  84\n|year record high F =124\n|Jan high F =  68\n|Feb high F =  73\n|Mar high F =  79\n|Apr high F =  88\n|May high F =  98\n|Jun high F = 107\n|Jul high F = 108\n|Aug high F = 106\n|Sep high F = 102\n|Oct high F =  90\n|Nov high F =  77\n|Dec high F =  67\n|year high F =\n|Jan low F = 36\n|Feb low F = 39\n|Mar low F = 44\n|Apr low F = 50\n|May low F = 59\n|Jun low F = 68\n|Jul low F = 77\n|Aug low F = 76\n|Sep low F = 68\n|Oct low F = 54\n|Nov low F = 42\n|Dec low F = 35\n|year low F =\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation inch = 0.83\n|Feb precipitation inch = 0.91\n|Mar precipitation inch = 1.00\n|Apr precipitation inch = 0.28\n|May precipitation inch = 0.17\n|Jun precipitation inch = 0.08\n|Jul precipitation inch = 0.98\n|Aug precipitation inch = 0.96\n|Sep precipitation inch = 0.72\n|Oct precipitation inch = 0.47\n|Nov precipitation inch = 0.58\n|Dec precipitation inch = 0.97\n|year precipitation inch =7.98\n|source 1 = The Weather Channel<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USAZ0131|title= Monthly Averages for Maricopa, AZ | publisher=Weather.com |year=2010 |accessdate=September 17, 2012}}</ref>\n|date=September 2012\n}}\n\n===Surrounding municipalities===\n{{Geographic location\n|Northwest = [[Goodyear, Arizona|Goodyear]]\n|North     = [[Gila River Indian Community]]\n|Northeast = Gila River Indian Community\n|West      = [[Ak-Chin Village, Arizona|Ak-Chin Village]]\n|Center    = Maricopa\n|South     = [[Stanfield, Arizona|Stanfield]]\n|Southwest = Palo Verde Mountains\n|Southeast = [[Casa Grande, Arizona|Casa Grande]]\n|East      = Gila River Indian Community\n}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|2000= 1040\n|2010= 43482\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=50024\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=<center>U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref></center>\n}}\n\nAs of the census of 2010, there were 43,482 people, 14,359 households, and 11,110 families residing in the city. The population density was 1,356.8 people per square mile (526.4/km<sup>2</sup>). There were 17,240 housing units at an average density of 540.4 per square mile (208.7/km<sup>2</sup>). The racial makeup of the city was 70.2% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 9.7% [[African American (U.S. Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 2.0% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 4.1% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.3% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 8.5% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 5.3% from two or more races. 24.4% of the population is [[Hispanics in the United States|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 14,359 households out of which 47.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 37.5% were married couples living together, 10.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 22.6% were non-families. 15.6% of all households were made up of individuals and 2.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 3.03 and the average family size was 3.38.<ref name=\"factfinder2.census\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid%3DDEC_10_DP_DPDP1%26prodType%3Dtable |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 23, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305164937/http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_DP_DPDP1&prodType=table |archivedate=March 5, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 32.5% under the age of 18, 6.2% from 18 to 24, 35% from 25 to 44, 19.8% from 45 to 64, and 6.5% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 31.2 years. For every 100 females, there were 98.5 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.8 males.\n\nAccording to 2009 Census Bureau estimates, the median income for a household in the city was $67,692, and the median income for a family was $69,818.  The per capita income for the city was $27,618. About 3.7% of families and 5.2% of the population were below the poverty line.\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n=== Roads ===\nMaricopa is primarily served by [[Arizona State Route 347]], a north-south highway that connects to [[Interstate 10 in Arizona|Interstate 10]], approximately 14 miles north of Maricopa, as well as [[Arizona State Route 84]] 11 miles south of Maricopa. State Route 84 then ends at [[Interstate 8]] approximately 6 miles west of State Route 347. Within Maricopa, State Route 347 is John Wayne Parkway. As it leaves the city for the [[Gila River Indian Community]] to the north or the [[Ak-Chin Indian Community]] to the south, the road changes names to Maricopa Road. A portion of old State Route 347 within Maricopa also exists as Maricopa Road.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinalcentral.com/maricopa_monitor/news/addresses-for-maricopa-road-properties-to-officially-change-dec/article_069a5354-dc5b-549e-8ce7-52636a887fe4.html|title=Addresses for Maricopa Road properties to officially change Dec. 1|last=|first=|date=|website=PinalCentral|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMaricopa is also served by [[Arizona State Route 238]], which connects Maricopa to the town of [[Mobile, Arizona|Mobile]], which is incorporated into the city of [[Goodyear, Arizona|Goodyear]]. Past Mobile, State Route 238 becomes a county route that connects to [[Arizona State Route 85]] in [[Gila Bend, Arizona|Gila Bend]]. State Route 238 and Mobile Road designations are used interchangeably. State Route 238 ends at State Route 347, and continues east as Smith-Enke Road, a major east-west corridor for the city of Maricopa. Maricopa-Casa Grande Highway also makes up a major corridor for the city, connecting it to the city of [[Casa Grande, Arizona|Casa Grande]]. This road parallels the Union Pacific Railroad at a diagonal, ultimately becoming Plainview Street within Maricopa and Cottonwood Lane in Casa Grande.\n\n=== Rail ===\n[[File:California-Zephyr-MaricopaAZ.JPG|thumb|California Zephyr railcar at the Maricopa, AZ [[Amtrak]] station]]Maricopa is located on a Union Pacific Railroad line. The city is currently the closest stop to [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] on [[Amtrak]]'s ''[[Sunset Limited]]'' and ''[[Texas Eagle]]'' trains. The [[Maricopa (Amtrak station)|Maricopa depot]] opened in 2001, originally in a converted passenger rail car but now in a metal building.\n\n=== Utilities ===\nMaricopa is served by the following utilities:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maricopa-az.gov/our-city/residents/utilities-services-in-maricopa|title=Utilities & Services in Maricopa|last=|first=|date=|website=City of Maricopa, AZ|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n* Cable: Orbitel Communications\n* Electricity: Electrical District #3\n* Natural Gas: [[Southwest Gas]]\n* Telephone/DSL: [[CenturyLink]]\n* Water: Global Water (Santa Cruz Water Company, Palo Verde Utilities), Maricopa Domestic Water Improvement District\n\n=== Bus ===\nThe City of Maricopa operates the City Of Maricopa Express Transit (COMET), which provides local bus service.<ref>{{Cite web| title = COMET Transit System {{!}} Maricopa, AZ| accessdate = 2020-02-03| url = https://www.maricopa-az.gov/departments/development-services/transportation/comet-transit-system}}</ref>\n\n==Municipal organization==\nMaricopa is governed by a Council-Manager form of government. This type of government structure combines the political leadership of elected officials with the managerial experience of an appointed professional manager. The City Council and City Manager work as partners to direct and guide local government.\n\nThe Maricopa City Council consists of the Mayor and six City Council members. The Mayor is elected to serve a four-year term and the City Council members are elected to serve four-year terms on a rotating basis. City Council meetings are held on the first and third Tuesdays of the month.\n\nThere are 10 citizen advisory groups that guide the Maricopa City Council on a myriad of activity. They are the Board of Adjustment, Heritage District Advisory Committee, Industrial Development Authority Board, Merit Board, Parks, Recreation and Library Advisory Committee, Planning and Zoning Commission, Public Safety Personnel Retirement System Board, Transportation Advisory Committee and the Youth Council. Selection to these groups is by City Council action.\n\nThe City is organized into nine departments: the City Manager's Office, the City Clerk's Office, Community Services, Development Services, Economic Development, Finance, Fire, Human Services and the Police Department. More than 250 individuals work for the municipality.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Civic and nonprofit organizations==\n*F.O.R. Maricopa - local [[food bank]]\n*Maricopa Gun Club- local gun club\n*Maricopa Historical Society - area historical organization\n*Maricopa Motorcycle Riders  - local group of riders; all bikes allowed\n*Maricopa Seniors  - area senior citizen group\n* [http://www.momdoccharities.org/ MomDoc Charities]\n*[[Pet Social Worker / Tails of Hope Rescue]] - local animal [[rescue group]]\n*Recycling Association of Maricopa (R.A.M.) - community drop-off recycling\n*Thunderbird Arena Community Council (TACC) - area organization supporting the renovation of the Thunderbird Farms Arena\n\n==Education facilities==\n\n=== Public school districts ===\n\n*[[Maricopa Unified School District]]\n*[[Mobile Elementary School District]]\n\n=== Public elementary schools ===\n\n* Butterfield Elementary School\n* Mobile Elementary School\n* Maricopa Elementary School\n* Pima Butte Elementary School\n* Saddleback Elementary School\n* Santa Cruz Elementary School\n* Santa Rosa Elementary School\n\n=== Public middle schools ===\n\n* Desert Wind Middle School\n* Maricopa Wells Middle School\n\n=== Public high school ===\n\n*[[Maricopa High School]]\n\n=== Charter schools ===\n\n* Graysmark Academy\n* Holsteiner Agricultural School\n* Leading Edge Academy\n* [https://maricopa.legacytraditional.org/ Legacy Traditional School-Maricopa Campus]\n* Sequoia Pathway Academy\n\n=== Community college ===\n\n* [[Central Arizona College]]\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Bristol Palin]], daughter of former Vice Presidential candidate [[Sarah Palin]], bought a house and lived in Maricopa for two years before returning to Alaska.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/40804372/ns/us_news-life/|title=New Ariz. homeowner: Bristol Palin|date=December 24, 2010|publisher=MSNBC|work=Today|accessdate=January 2, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227085708/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/40804372/ns/us_news-life|archivedate=December 27, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>[http://www.zillow.com/blog/2012-05-08/bristol-palin-no-longer-an-arizona-homeowner/ \"Bristol Palin No Longer an Arizona Homeowner\"]. ''Zillow''. May 2012.</ref>\n*Former State Senator [[Steve Smith (Arizona politician)|Steve Smith]] resides in Maricopa.\"\nTony Beets, from the show Gold Rush, Lives in Maricopa.(County land records)\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.maricopa-az.gov/ City of Maricopa]\n\n{{Pinal County, Arizona}}\n{{Phoenix Metropolitan Area}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Former census-designated places in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Cities in Pinal County, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Phoenix metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 2003]]\n[[Category:Maricopa, Arizona]]\n", "name_user": "Lam-ang", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed GNIS ID, remove file prefix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maricopa,_Arizona"}
{"title_page": "Selwyn Image", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Selwyn Image\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            =  Selwyn_Image_1900.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Selwyn Image 1900\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_date       = 17 February 1849\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_place      = [[Bodiam]], Sussex\n| death_date       =  {{death date and age |df=y|1930|8|21 |1849|2|17 }}\n| death_place      =  \n| nationality      = British\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       =  \n| known_for        = [[Stained glass]] design, book illustraton, writing, poetry \n| style            = \n| movement         = [[Arts and Crafts Movement]]\n| spouse           = Janet Image\n| awards           = \n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Selwyn Image''' (17 February 1849, [[Bodiam]], Sussex \u2013 21 August 1930, London) was an important British artist, designer, writer and poet associated with the [[Arts and Crafts Movement]]. He designed stained glass windows, furniture, embroidery, and was an illustrator of books. Image was the first [[Slade Professor of Fine Art]] at [[Oxford]] from 1910 to 1916.\n\n==Early life and education==\nSelwyn Image was born in [[Bodiam]], Sussex on 17 February 1849 to the Reverend John Image (c. 1802\u20131878), vicar of [[Bodiam]] and Mary Maxwell (''nee'' Hinds c. 1807\u20131857).<ref name=\"Oxford dictionary of National Biography\">{{cite web |last1=Jones |first1=Helen Caroline |title=Image, Selwyn (1849\u20131930) |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-34093 |website=Oxford dictionary of National Biography |accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref> He attended [[Marlborough College]] and the [[New College, Oxford]] in 1868 where he studied drawing under [[John Ruskin]].<ref name=\"British Museum\">{{cite web |title=Selwyn Image (Biographical Details) |url=http://www.britishmuseum.org/research/search_the_collection_database/term_details.aspx?bioId=120211 |website=British Museum |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref> Intending on entering the clergy and following his father as Vicar of [[Bodiam]], Image took Holy Orders at the age of 24. He was ordained deacon in 1872, and priest the next year. He was a curate at [[Tottenham]] and later at [[St Anne's Church, Soho|St. Anne's, Soho]]. Image began studying art with [[Arthur Heygate Mackmurdo|A. H. Mackmurdo]] and [[John Ruskin|Ruskin's]] assistant, Arthur Burgess in 1880.<ref name=\"Matthew Tildesley\">{{cite thesis |type=PhD|last= Tildesley|first=Matthew B. |year=2007 |title= The century guild hobby horse and Oscar Wilde: a study of British little magazines, 1884\u20131897  |publisher=Durham University|}}</ref> Image eventually abandoned the clergy in 1882.<ref name=morris/><ref name=\"Benezit Dictionary\">{{cite book |title=Benezit Dictionary of British Graphic Artists and Illustrators, Volume 1 |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0199923052 |pages=1344 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=05C02RhJZCkC&pg=PA601&lpg=PA601&dq=selwyn+image+bodiam+sussex&source=bl&ots=QLmga_iMb9&sig=S_1f4uxOVk_aIMm_HLS34oyQRfw&hl=en&sa=X&sqi=2&ved=0ahUKEwjx84-6pLDcAhVn0oMKHSrQBPIQ6AEIUzAL#v=onepage&q=selwyn%20image%20bodiam%20sussex&f=false |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==The Century Guild of Artists==\n\nHe founded the [[Century Guild of Artists]] in London with prominent architect and designer [[Arthur Heygate Mackmurdo|A. H. Mackmurdo]]. With [[Arthur Heygate Mackmurdo|  Mackmurdo]], Image established the Guild's workshops which produced furniture, wallpaper, primarily domestic design such as furniture, stained glass, metalwork, and decorative painting. Image was co-editor of the Guild's magazine, ''[[The Hobby Horse]]'', from 1886 to 1892.<ref name=morris>{{cite book|publisher=William Morris Gallery Walthamstow|title=Catalogue of A. H. Mackmurdo and the Century Guild Collection |year=1967|page=48}}</ref> He was an active member of the [[Art Workers' Guild]] in London and became a Master of the guild in 1900..<ref name=\"Benezit Dictionary\" />\n\n==Stained glass designer==\n[[File:Angel_window_-_geograph.org.uk_-_880160_(cropped).jpg|200px|right]]\nOne of Image's first [[stained glass]] designs, ''The Seasons'', manufactured by [[James Powell & Sons]], was exhibited at the [[Exposition Universelle (1878)|Paris International Exhibition]] in 1878. Image's designs were influenced by the work of [[William Morris]].  Image's early designs, composed of individual figures against a floral background, was inspired by Morris's previous work. Image described one of [[Morris & Co.]] earliest stained glass commissions, one of a pair of two-light windows (1862) depicting the four archangels at St. Michael and All Angels church in [[Brighton]] 'as one of the finest modern windows I know of.'\" The early window, designed by [[Ford Madox Brown]] was the inspiraton for Image's ''Archangel'' window at [[Mortehoe]].<ref name=\"Peter Cormack\">{{cite book |last1=Cormack |first1=Peter |title=Arts & Crafts Stained Glass |date=2015 |publisher=Paul Mellon Centre for Studies in British Art |isbn=978-0300209709 |pages=354}}</ref>\n\nThe basis of Image's stained glass design was a \"simplicity of treatment, not only in figure drawing and ornament\u2014which closely match his contemporary graphic work, such as for the Century Guild [[The Hobby Horse]]\u2014but also in the use of leading. In an article published in [[The Hobby Horse]] in 1890, Image expounded his principles of stained glass design, emphasizing that qualities of 'richness and brilliance of effect....in no small measure depend upon the management of the leads'\".<ref name=\"Peter Cormack\" />\n\nImage and well-known stained glass artist, [[Christopher Whall]] met in the 1880s and became lasting friends. Whall and Image were among the earliest pioneers and important contributors to the [[Arts and Crafts Movement]]. Image designed fewer than thirty windows during his career, but a number of cartoons (designs) were displayed at [[Arts and Crafts Exhibition Society|Arts and Crafts Exhibitions]]. Several of Image's designs were illustrated in books and magazines where Image acquired a wide following. [[Christopher Whall]] included one of Image's cartoons in his influential manual ''Stained Glass Work'' (1905), \"as an example of the 'simple and severe' style of drawing best suited to the medium.\"<ref name=\"Peter Cormack\" />\n\nImage was influential in the work of a number of [[stained glass]] artists, including two women: [[Mary J. Newill]] (1860\u20131947) and Helen Coombe (1864\u20131937). Mary J. Newill was a talented artist-craftsman who trained at the [[Birmingham Municipal School of Art]] in the 1880s and 1890s. Helen Coombe (1864\u20131937) was a student of Image at the [[Slade School of Fine Art]] and her design for the ''Mary and Martha'' window was displayed at the 1896 Arts and Crafts Exhibition and showed the influence of Image as artistic mentor.<ref name=\"Peter Cormack\" />\n\n==Writer, lecturer, and poet==\n\nImage was an influential writer on design and the first Slade Professor of Fine Arts at Oxford from 1910 to 1916.<ref name=\"Benezit Dictionary\" />\n\nBetween December 1887 and February 1888, Image gave a series of four lectures on Modern Art at Willis' Rooms. [[Oscar Wilde]] attended at least one of this series, and reviewed the second lecture in the ''[[Sunday Times]]'' on 25 January 1888.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Tildesley, Matthew B. |title=The Sketches of Dorian Gray : Oscar Wilde and The Century Guild Hobby Horse|journal= The Wildean|issue= 37|date= July 2010}}</ref>\n\nImage published a number of essays, contributed introductions and chapters to scholarly publications, and published a poetry collection, ''Poems and Carols'' in 1894.\n\n==Other work==\nImage's line-block design for the cover of the inaugural 1884 issue of the Hobby Horse, the Guild's publication, is widely known. Other celebrated works include the design of embroideries for the Royal School of Needlework and bookbindings such as that for the novel Stefania (1893)\".<ref name=\"Oxford Index\" />\n\nIn 1900, Image was hired as a designer for the Glasgow furniture manufacturer, Wylie and Lochead.<ref name=\"Benezit Dictionary\" />\n\n==Death and legacy==\n\nImage died at [[Holloway, London|Holloway]] on 21 August 1930.<ref name=morris/> Two years after his death, selected poems and later his letters, edited by [[Arthur Heygate Mackmurdo|Mackmurdo]] was published.<ref name=\"Oxford Index\">{{cite web |title=OVERVIEW Selwyn Image (1849\u20141930) designer |url=http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.20110803095958513 |website=Oxford Index |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Stained glass work==\n*St Mary's, [[Mortehoe]], Devon (1888)<ref name=\"Benezit Dictionary\" />\n* ''Wise Virgins'', St. Michael and All Angels, [[Waterford, Hertfordshire]] (1888)<ref name=\"Peter Cormack\" />\n*''Archangels'', St. Cuthbert's church, [[Darlington]], [[Durham, England|Durham]], England (1889)<ref name=\"Peter Cormack\" />\n*St. Peter's Church, [[Cranbourne, Berkshire]]\n*''Angels'' & ''Transfiguration'', St. Andrew's, [[Much Hadham]], Hertfordshire (1891)\n*''Brownies'', Solham House, Newmarket (1895), (currently on display at the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]])<ref name=\"Victoria and Albert\">{{cite web |title=Brownies |url=https://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O8165/brownies-oriel-window-selwyn-image/ |website=Victoria and Albert Museum Collections |accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref>\n*St. Luke's Church, [[Camberwell]]<ref name=\"Benezit Dictionary\" />\n\n==Selected publications==\n*{{cite book |last1=Image |first1=Selwyn |title=Poems and Carols (1894) |date=1894 |publisher=E. Matthews |location=London |pages=47}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Image |first1=Selwyn |title=Some Reflections on the Art of Thomas Rowlandson & George Morland |date=1929 |publisher=Print Collector's Club |location=London}}\n*{{cite book |editor-last1=Mackmurdo |editor-first1=Arthur Heygate|title=The Poems of Selwyn Image |date=1932 |publisher=Elkin, Matthews and Marrot |location=London |edition=1st}}<ref name=morris/>\n*Poems (1932), edited by [[Arthur Heygate Mackmurdo]]<ref name=morris/>\n*{{cite book |editor-last1=Mackmurdo |editor-first1=Arthur Heygate|title=Selwyn Image Letters |date=1932 |publisher=Grant Richards Pronto Limited |location=London |pages=219}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Miles |first1=Alfred H. |title=The Sacred Poets of the Nineteenth Century Edward Hayes Plumptre to Selwyn Image |date=2011 |publisher=BiblioLife |isbn=978-1113886460 |pages=440}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Image, Selwyn}}\n[[Category:1849 births]]\n[[Category:1930 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bodiam]]\n[[Category:19th-century English Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:Slade Professors of Fine Art (University of Oxford)]]\n[[Category:British stained glass artists and manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of New College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:People educated at Brighton College]]\n[[Category:People educated at Marlborough College]]\n[[Category:English male poets]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Selwyn Image\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            =  Selwyn_Image_1900.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Selwyn Image 1900\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_date       = 17 February 1849\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_place      = [[Bodiam]], Sussex\n| death_date       =  {{death date and age |df=y|1930|8|21 |1849|2|17 }}\n| death_place      =  \n| nationality      = British\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       =  \n| known_for        = [[Stained glass]] design, book illustraton, writing, poetry \n| style            = \n| movement         = [[Arts and Crafts Movement]]\n| spouse           = Janet Image\n| awards           = \n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Selwyn Image''' (17 February 1849, [[Bodiam]], Sussex \u2013 21 August 1930, London) was an important British artist, designer, writer and poet associated with the [[Arts and Crafts Movement]]. He designed stained glass windows, furniture, embroidery, and was an illustrator of books. Image was the first [[Slade Professor of Fine Art]] at [[Oxford]] from 1910 to 1916.\n\n==Early life and education==\nSelwyn Image was born in [[Bodiam]], Sussex on 17 February 1849 to the Reverend John Image (c. 1802\u20131878), vicar of [[Bodiam]] and Mary Maxwell (''nee'' Hinds c. 1807\u20131857).<ref name=\"Oxford dictionary of National Biography\">{{cite web |last1=Jones |first1=Helen Caroline |title=Image, Selwyn (1849\u20131930) |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-34093 |website=Oxford dictionary of National Biography |accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref> He attended [[Marlborough College]] and the [[New College, Oxford]] in 1868 where he studied drawing under [[John Ruskin]].<ref name=\"British Museum\">{{cite web |title=Selwyn Image (Biographical Details) |url=http://www.britishmuseum.org/research/search_the_collection_database/term_details.aspx?bioId=120211 |website=British Museum |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref> Intending on entering the clergy and following his father as Vicar of [[Bodiam]], Image took Holy Orders at the age of 24. He was ordained deacon in 1872, and priest the next year. He was a curate at [[Tottenham]] and later at [[St Anne's Church, Soho|St. Anne's, Soho]]. Image began studying art with [[Arthur Heygate Mackmurdo|A. H. Mackmurdo]] and [[John Ruskin|Ruskin's]] assistant, Arthur Burgess in 1880.<ref name=\"Matthew Tildesley\">{{cite thesis |type=PhD|last= Tildesley|first=Matthew B. |year=2007 |title= The century guild hobby horse and Oscar Wilde: a study of British little magazines, 1884\u20131897  |publisher=Durham University|}}</ref> Image eventually abandoned the clergy in 1882.<ref name=morris/><ref name=\"Benezit Dictionary\">{{cite book |title=Benezit Dictionary of British Graphic Artists and Illustrators, Volume 1 |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0199923052 |pages=1344 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=05C02RhJZCkC&pg=PA601&lpg=PA601&dq=selwyn+image+bodiam+sussex&source=bl&ots=QLmga_iMb9&sig=S_1f4uxOVk_aIMm_HLS34oyQRfw&hl=en&sa=X&sqi=2&ved=0ahUKEwjx84-6pLDcAhVn0oMKHSrQBPIQ6AEIUzAL#v=onepage&q=selwyn%20image%20bodiam%20sussex&f=false |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==The Century Guild of Artists==\n\nHe founded the [[Century Guild of Artists]] in London with prominent architect and designer [[Arthur Heygate Mackmurdo|A. H. Mackmurdo]]. With [[Arthur Heygate Mackmurdo|  Mackmurdo]], Image established the Guild's workshops which produced furniture, wallpaper, primarily domestic design such as furniture, stained glass, metalwork, and decorative painting. Image was co-editor of the Guild's magazine, ''[[The Hobby Horse]]'', from 1886 to 1892.<ref name=morris>{{cite book|publisher=William Morris Gallery Walthamstow|title=Catalogue of A. H. Mackmurdo and the Century Guild Collection |year=1967|page=48}}</ref> He was an active member of the [[Art Workers' Guild]] in London and became a Master of the guild in 1900..<ref name=\"Benezit Dictionary\" />\n\n==Stained glass designer==\n[[File:Angel_window_-_geograph.org.uk_-_880160_(cropped).jpg|200px|right]]\nOne of Image's first [[stained glass]] designs, ''The Seasons'', manufactured by [[James Powell & Sons]], was exhibited at the [[Exposition Universelle (1878)|Paris International Exhibition]] in 1878. Image's designs were influenced by the work of [[William Morris]].  Image's early designs, composed of individual figures against a floral background, was inspired by Morris's previous work. Image described one of [[Morris & Co.]] earliest stained glass commissions, one of a pair of two-light windows (1862) depicting the four archangels at St. Michael and All Angels church in [[Brighton]] 'as one of the finest modern windows I know of.'\" The early window, designed by [[Ford Madox Brown]] was the inspiraton for Image's ''Archangel'' window at [[Mortehoe]].<ref name=\"Peter Cormack\">{{cite book |last1=Cormack |first1=Peter |title=Arts & Crafts Stained Glass |date=2015 |publisher=Paul Mellon Centre for Studies in British Art |isbn=978-0300209709 |pages=354}}</ref>\n\nThe basis of Image's stained glass design was a \"simplicity of treatment, not only in figure drawing and ornament\u2014which closely match his contemporary graphic work, such as for the Century Guild [[The Hobby Horse]]\u2014but also in the use of leading. In an article published in [[The Hobby Horse]] in 1890, Image expounded his principles of stained glass design, emphasizing that qualities of 'richness and brilliance of effect....in no small measure depend upon the management of the leads'\".<ref name=\"Peter Cormack\" />\n\nImage and well-known stained glass artist, [[Christopher Whall]] met in the 1880's and became lasting friends. Whall and Image were among the earliest pioneers and important contributors to the [[Arts and Crafts Movement]]. Image designed fewer than thirty windows during his career, but a number of cartoons (designs) were displayed at [[Arts and Crafts Exhibition Society|Arts and Crafts Exhibitions]]. Several of Image's designs were illustrated in books and magazines where Image acquired a wide following. [[Christopher Whall]] included one of Image's cartoons in his influential manual ''Stained Glass Work'' (1905), \"as an example of the 'simple and severe' style of drawing best suited to the medium.\"<ref name=\"Peter Cormack\" />\n\nImage was influential in the work of a number of [[stained glass]] artists, including two women: [[Mary J. Newill]] (1860\u20131947) and Helen Coombe (1864\u20131937). Mary J. Newill was a talented artist-craftsman who trained at the [[Birmingham Municipal School of Art]] in the 1880's and 1890's. Helen Coombe (1864\u20131937) was a student of Image at the [[Slade School of Fine Art]] and her design for the ''Mary and Martha'' window was displayed at the 1896 Arts and Crafts Exhibition and showed the influence of Image as artistic mentor.<ref name=\"Peter Cormack\" />\n\n==Writer, lecturer, and poet==\n\nImage was an influential writer on design and the first Slade Professor of Fine Arts at Oxford from 1910 to 1916.<ref name=\"Benezit Dictionary\" />\n\nBetween December 1887 and February 1888, Image gave a series of four lectures on Modern Art at Willis' Rooms. [[Oscar Wilde]] attended at least one of this series, and reviewed the second lecture in the ''[[Sunday Times]]'' on 25 January 1888.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Tildesley, Matthew B. |title=The Sketches of Dorian Gray : Oscar Wilde and The Century Guild Hobby Horse|journal= The Wildean|issue= 37|date= July 2010}}</ref>\n\nImage published a number of essays, contributed introductions and chapters to scholarly publications, and published a poetry collection, ''Poems and Carols'' in 1894.\n\n==Other work==\nImage's line-block design for the cover of the inaugural 1884 issue of the Hobby Horse, the Guild's publication, is widely known. Other celebrated works include the design of embroideries for the Royal School of Needlework and bookbindings such as that for the novel Stefania (1893)\".<ref name=\"Oxford Index\" />\n\nIn 1900, Image was hired as a designer for the Glasgow furniture manufacturer, Wylie and Lochead.<ref name=\"Benezit Dictionary\" />\n\n==Death and legacy==\n\nImage died at [[Holloway, London|Holloway]] on 21 August 1930.<ref name=morris/> Two years after his death, selected poems and later his letters, edited by [[Arthur Heygate Mackmurdo|Mackmurdo]] was published.<ref name=\"Oxford Index\">{{cite web |title=OVERVIEW Selwyn Image (1849\u20141930) designer |url=http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.20110803095958513 |website=Oxford Index |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Stained glass work==\n*St Mary's, [[Mortehoe]], Devon (1888)<ref name=\"Benezit Dictionary\" />\n* ''Wise Virgins'', St. Michael and All Angels, [[Waterford, Hertfordshire]] (1888)<ref name=\"Peter Cormack\" />\n*''Archangels'', St. Cuthbert's church, [[Darlington]], [[Durham, England|Durham]], England (1889)<ref name=\"Peter Cormack\" />\n*St. Peter's Church, [[Cranbourne, Berkshire]]\n*''Angels'' & ''Transfiguration'', St. Andrew's, [[Much Hadham]], Hertfordshire (1891)\n*''Brownies'', Solham House, Newmarket (1895), (currently on display at the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]])<ref name=\"Victoria and Albert\">{{cite web |title=Brownies |url=https://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O8165/brownies-oriel-window-selwyn-image/ |website=Victoria and Albert Museum Collections |accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref>\n*St. Luke's Church, [[Camberwell]]<ref name=\"Benezit Dictionary\" />\n\n==Selected publications==\n*{{cite book |last1=Image |first1=Selwyn |title=Poems and Carols (1894) |date=1894 |publisher=E. Matthews |location=London |pages=47}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Image |first1=Selwyn |title=Some Reflections on the Art of Thomas Rowlandson & George Morland |date=1929 |publisher=Print Collector's Club |location=London}}\n*{{cite book |editor-last1=Mackmurdo |editor-first1=Arthur Heygate|title=The Poems of Selwyn Image |date=1932 |publisher=Elkin, Matthews and Marrot |location=London |edition=1st}}<ref name=morris/>\n*Poems (1932), edited by [[Arthur Heygate Mackmurdo]]<ref name=morris/>\n*{{cite book |editor-last1=Mackmurdo |editor-first1=Arthur Heygate|title=Selwyn Image Letters |date=1932 |publisher=Grant Richards Pronto Limited |location=London |pages=219}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Miles |first1=Alfred H. |title=The Sacred Poets of the Nineteenth Century Edward Hayes Plumptre to Selwyn Image |date=2011 |publisher=BiblioLife |isbn=978-1113886460 |pages=440}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Image, Selwyn}}\n[[Category:1849 births]]\n[[Category:1930 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bodiam]]\n[[Category:19th-century English Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:Slade Professors of Fine Art (University of Oxford)]]\n[[Category:British stained glass artists and manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of New College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:People educated at Brighton College]]\n[[Category:People educated at Marlborough College]]\n[[Category:English male poets]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStained glass designer:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1880's and 1890's \u2192 1880s and 1890s, 1880's \u2192 1880s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Selwyn_Image"}
